<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 00:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, June 21, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Anti-Terrorism Center Set-Up in Russia
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- At their one-day Kremlin summit on Wednesday, the leaders of
the Commonwealth of Independent States established a joint anti-terrorist center
and moved ahead with long-stalled plans for a free-trade zone. The center, which
is to coordinate efforts to combat organized crime and insurgencies throughout
the former Soviet republics, will be located in Moscow and headed by a general
from the Russian Federal Security Service, a KGB successor agency.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House Vote Affects Gun Agreement
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a blow to the landmark agreement among the nation's
largest gun maker, the Clinton administration and hundreds of communities, the
House voted Wednesday to bar the federal government from helping to attract more
muncipalities to the pact. By a 218-207 vote, the House voted to prevent the
government from spending any money for the Communities for Safer Guns Coalition.
In return for Smith &AMP; Wesson's promise to use gun-safety devices and sales
practices, the 411 localities that have so far joined the coalition have agreed
to make the company's firearms the preferred gun for their law enforcement
agencies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Supports Oil Price Probe
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- George W. Bush voiced support for an investigation of
soaring gasoline prices, but he put most of the blame on the Clinton
administration's failure to convince foreign crude producers to ''open the
spigots.'' ''I do think it's fair to have the FTC (Federal Trade Commission)
investigate,'' Bush told reporters Wednesday, adding that the results would be
''healthy'' for the debate about prices that have climbed above $2 per gallon in
Chicago and Milwaukee. His Democratic rival for the presidency, Al Gore,
countered that Bush has come late to the issue.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
OPEC Is Hiking Oil Output
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- OPEC members agreed Wednesday to boost official crude
oil production by 3 percent, a move unlikely to provide U.S. drivers with
summertime relief from record-high gasoline prices. Ten OPEC members voted to
increase the group's daily quota by 708,000 barrels beginning July 1. ''Gas will
stay as tight as ever, and it will only come down when the driving season
ends,'' said Leo Drollas, chief economist for the London-based Center for Global
Energy Studies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jury Hears 911 Tape in Davidian Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WACO, Texas (AP) -- The panic and terror within the walls of the Branch
Davidian complex were relived Wednesday as the audiotaped drama of the first
moments of the government's 1993 raid was played in a multimillion-dollar
wrongful death trial. ''There are 75 men around us and they are shooting at us
at Mount Carmel!'' sect member Wayne Martin screamed in the telephone. ''Tell
them there are children and women in here and to call it off!'' The exchange was
captured on 911 tapes by the McLennan County Sheriff's Office, whom Martin
called when shooting started on Feb. 28, 1993.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fla. Executes Man Who Had Reprieve
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   STARKE, Fla. (AP) -- A man who killed a bailiff in a 1984 courtroom shooting
and thought he was Jesus Christ was executed by injection Wednesday, one day
after he received a reprieve while strapped to the gurney in the death chamber.
Thomas Provenzano had been granted the stay yesterday, 11 minutes before the
scheduled execution. A three-judge panel U.S. Court of Appeals in Atlanta, which
had given no reason for its stay, dissolved the order this morning and Gov. Jeb
Bush rescheduled the execution.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Gain in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks edged higher early Thursday as the market was
supported by an advance on Wall Street. The Nikkei gained 28.93 points to
17,239.01. In New York Wednesday, the Nasdaq climbed 50.65 to close at 4,064.01.
The Dow gained 62.58 to 10,497.74.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rockies Defeat Reds 6-4
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Neifi Perez and Darren Bragg singled home runs and Ken
Griffey Jr.'s throwing error let in another as the Colorado Rockies rallied in
the eighth inning for a 6-4 victory Wednesday over the slumping Cincinnati Reds.
Colorado got its eighth victory in 11 games by taking advantage of another wild
performance by reliever Scott Williamson (2-4), who's failing to duplicate his
NL rookie of the year season. The Reds have lost 12 of 14, failing to win
consecutive games since June 3-4. The tailspin has dropped them a distant second
in the NL Central.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
