<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President helps raise soft money for wife's Senate bid  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - President Clinton played the role of
''surrogate-in-chief'' Wednesday night, helping to raise $200,000
for his wife's New York Senate campaign at a private reception for
wealthy donors.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the two dozen people - who had paid $10,000 or more
each to attend - that Hillary Clinton would make a good senator
because she understands the problems faced by working parents.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the whole cluster of family issues will be very big in
the next decade,'' Clinton told the group at the Georgetown home of
two top Democratic donors. ''She spent 30 years working on this
stuff ...
</P>
<P>
   ''In a lot of ways, she's better than I am. She knows some
things I don't know. She will do a great job at this.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser was hosted by Elizabeth Frawley Bagley, a former
Clinton ambassador to Portugal, and her husband, R.J. Reynolds
tobacco heir and foundation president Smith Bagley. The Bagleys had
come under criticism earlier this year for having Elian Gonzalez,
the Cuban refugee boy at the center of a bitter custody battle,
visit their posh home.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not mention Gonzalez or Cuba in his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Clinton spoke at a fund-raiser for the Irish
American Democrats, a group that has pledged to give his wife's
campaign $10,000 and a similar amount to Vice President Al Gore's
bid for the White House. The Irish group gave top Democratic
fund-raiser Terry McAuliffe an award, and Clinton spoke of his role
in the negotiations that led to the Protestant-Catholic power
sharing agreement in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ''None of the elitists thought we ought to do it, but all us
blue-collar rednecks thought it was a good idea,'' Clinton told the
crowd of about 150, who had paid up to $1,000 each to attend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
