<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox 9, Yankees 7  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD ULMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Yankees relievers Jason Grimsley and Mike Stanton
couldn't find the plate. Red Sox runners did it five times in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   After wasting a lead in the top half of the seventh inning,
Boston rallied in the bottom half to beat New York 9-7 Wednesday
night after sleeping through the first two games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, coming off 22-1 and 3-0 wins, overcame a 4-2
deficit in the seventh on a run-scoring error by second baseman
Jeff Frye, an RBI grounder by Chuck Knoblauch -- making his first
start with New York at designated hitter -- and a sacrifice fly by
Paul O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley (3-2) relieved David Cone starting the bottom of the
inning, Nomar Garciaparra singled and Carl Everett walked.
</P>
<P>
   One out later, Scott Hatteberg's groundout tied it. Grimsley
then walked Brian Daubach intentionally and Manny Alexander
unintentionally, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton, who had walked just six batters in 32 innings coming,
walked Jose Offerman on four pitches and Jeff Frye on a 3-2 count
as Boston took a 7-5 lead. Trot Nixon followed with a two-run
double over the head of O'Neill in right.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams hit a two-run homer in the ninth off Derek Lowe,
just the third homer the reliever has allowed in 41 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Garces (3-0) pitched a scoreless inning as Boston stopped a
four-game losing streak and closed within a half-game of the
Yankees, who lead the AL East.
</P>
<P>
   Cone, just 1-6 in 14 starts, threw a run-scoring wild pitch in
the first and allowed Everett's RBI grounder following Nixon's
wind-blown triple over Williams in center.
</P>
<P>
   New York tied it on RBI singles by Chris Turner in the fifth off
Pete Schourek and Jorge Posada in the sixth off Hippolito Pichardo.
</P>
<P>
   Boston went ahead in the sixth on Alexander's RBI single and
Frye's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Frye singled in his third at-bat, one night after his
13-game hitting streak ended. ... Nixon was irate after he was
called out by John Hirschbeck on a close play in which Cone dropped
a throw from Posada, who was playing first, then picked it up as
Nixon hit the base. ... The Yankees hit just two balls out of the
infield in the first four innings against Schourek. ... Knoblauch
went 1-for-5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
