<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kendall Francois pleads guilty to eight murders to avoid death penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) - Kendall Francois, who admitted
strangling eight women and hiding their bodies in his home, pleaded
guilty Wednesday and avoided a possible death sentence in exchange
for life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Francois, 28, pleaded guilty to all 17 counts of the indictment,
which included 16 murder charges and one count of attempted
assault.
</P>
<P>
   Francois will be sentenced Aug. 7 to life imprisonment without
parole by Dutchess County Court Judge Thomas J. Dolan. He had been
scheduled to go on trial in the fall. It was revealed in court
Wednesday that Francois is HIV positive.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, Francois told police he solicited
the women for sex, then strangled them and hid their bodies inside
the garbage-strewn home he shared with his parents and younger
sister. The murders occurred over a 22-month period from October
1996 to August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The former middle school hall monitor was arrested in September
1998 after a woman he had brought to his home escaped. A search of
the family's home found the women's decomposing bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Francois had been considered a suspect earlier by police in the
cases of the missing women, but he had passed a lie detector test
when questioned by police.
</P>
<P>
   Francois admitted killing Sandra French, Catina Newmaster, Wendy
Meyers, Gina Barone, Catherine Marsh, Kathleen Hurley, Mary
Giaccone and Audrey Pugliese. All the women but one had a history
of prostitution and drug abuse, and had been reported missing from
a Poughkeepsie neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, Francois tried to plead guilty to the murders,
but Dolan refused the request because the district attorney had not
yet decided if he would seek the death penalty. Francois' lawyers
challenged that ruling as far as the state's highest court, which
upheld it in May.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney William Grady had indicated he would seek the
death penalty against Francois. On Wednesday, Grady said he
accepted the plea in part because of the victims' families who
wanted closure and a guarantee that Francois would die in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Grady said, Francois' psychiatric issues would
weigh heavily during the penalty phase of the trial and would be
difficult to refute, though Francois was not legally insane at the
time of the killings.
</P>
<P>
   ''In addition, many of the families do not want their children
and grandchildren needlessly exposed to the unsettling details of
his case that would be disclosed through a public trial,'' Grady
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kendall Francois' life will be spared but he will answer for
his actions,'' said Francois' lawyers Mark Harris and Glenda Grace.
''We hope that the finality of this sentence will bring some
closure to Kendall and his family and the families of his
victims.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 0023 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000622.0015 </DOCNO>
