<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bronx Dem leader: I could get excited about comptroller run  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - State Assemblyman Roberto Ramirez, the Bronx
Democratic Party chairman and a rising star in New York politics,
said Wednesday he ''could get excited'' about running for state
comptroller in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   But the Puerto Rican-born Ramirez cautioned that given
everything else he wants to do, ''I don't think it is within the
framework of political reality for me to be able to make such a
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Ramirez also said in an interview with The
Associated Press that, ''the harder you work, the better you do
your job, the more opportunities come up. And, if opportunities
come up, God knows I'm not shy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez is vacating his Assembly seat at the end of the year to
concentrate on electing Bronx Borough President Fernando Ferrer as
mayor of New York City next year and revamping the city council
there. He is also working to line up support for the possible run
for governor in 2002 by current state Comptroller H. Carl McCall.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier interview Wednesday on Albany's WROW-AM radio,
Ramirez ruled out a run next year for Bronx borough president or
New York's City Council. He had been mentioned as a possible
candidate for council speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would not hold any elected office for the next two years,''
Ramirez told the radio station.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, 50, was elected to the state Assembly in 1990 and in
1993 became the first Hispanic elected as a county party chairman
in New York. He surprised the state's political community with his
recent announcement that he would not seek re-election to his
Assembly seat.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez played a key role in helping state Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver survive an attempted coup last month by the No. 2
Democrat in the chamber, Michael Bragman. Bragman was stripped of
his post as Assembly majority leader by Silver and there was talk
that Ramirez might take over that job. Instead, Ramirez said he was
quitting the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez' comments about a possible run for state comptroller
came just hours before he hosted his annual Bronx Democratic Party
dinner, a fund-raising event expected to attract more than 1,500
people, including U.S. Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner comes at a time when the Bronx party is under strain
because of a primary challenge to veteran Democratic U.S. Rep.
Eliot Engel from state Sen. Larry Seabrook. Ramirez is backing
Seabrook, who is black in an increasingly black congressional
district. Engel is white.
</P>
<P>
   Should Ramirez become the Democrats' candidate for state
comptroller in 2002, the party ticket could have a minority and New
York City cast to it.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, who has homes in New York City and in Saratoga Springs,
is the only black ever elected to statewide office in New York.
State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer, who is white, also lives in
New York City. Spitzer has said he expects to seek a second term in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Also eyeing the governor's race on the Democratic side is
federal Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo. Anthony Nanula, Buffalo's
city comptroller, has been mentioned as a possible Democratic
candidate for state comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez made it clear Wednesday that talk of a statewide run by
him is very premature.
</P>
<P>
   ''The real threshold is not when you say you wish to run for
office, it's when people come up to you and say, 'You should run
for office,''' he explained. ''I don't hear a clamor out there for
Ramirez.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 0024 </TRAILER>
