<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State's top court refuses to hear abortion murder case  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - New York's highest court refused Wednesday
to hear the appeal of the first doctor ever found criminally
responsible for the death of a patient through a botched medical
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Without comment, Chief Judge Judith Kaye declined an appeal from
David Benjamin's lawyer to send the case to the full Court of
Appeals for a rehearing of Benjamin's conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin is serving a 25-year-to-life sentence in state prison
for the death of Guadalupe Negron. The mother of four bled to death
soon after Benjamin performed an abortion on her at his Queens
office in July 1993.
</P>
<P>
   It was later determined she had a three-inch rip in her uterus.
The doctor's receptionist testified at Benjamin's trial that the
doctor ignored the woman for more than an hour after the abortion.
She died at a nearby hospital.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the woman's death, Benjamin was facing state
disciplinary charges in connection with his treatment of other
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin's lawyer, Mark Baker of Manhattan, said he will
probably ask the Court of Appeals for ''reconsideration'' of Kaye's
determination. Such requests for another look at a denial of appeal
almost never succeed before the Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said his client refused a plea-bargain offer from
prosecutors involving second-degree manslaughter, a charge that
would have brought Benjamin a prison term of between three and nine
years.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, it was not right for Benjamin to eventually
be found guilty of a charge that he intentionally killed his
patient, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin's lawyers also argued before a lower court that the
jury at his trial was prejudiced when testimony about his previous
medical history was improperly allowed into evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors countered that Benjamin's treatment of Negron met
the legal test of ''depraved indifference'' murder and the fact he
was a doctor should not mean a lesser penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Queens County District Attorney Richard Brown said the Benjamin
case was the first time that a doctor was found guilty of murdering
a patient during a medical procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today's decision represents a solid victory for patients and
their families, who through the gross and depraved indifference of
their medical practitioners lose their lives or are seriously
injured during a medical procedure,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, such cases of medical treatment gone wrong are
handled through malpractice suits or disciplinary hearings in New
York state.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin, 63, is currently in Green Haven state prison. He will
not be eligible for parole until July 2018. He has lost his medical
license.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 0024 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000622.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With BC-HKN--Sabres-Adelphia  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Hopes for a thriving city waterfront ran
high Wednesday with news that Adelphia Communications Corp. and
government leaders had come to terms on an office complex that will
create 1,000 well-paying, high-tech jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today we begin the economic renaissance of downtown Buffalo,''
declared Charles Gargano, chairman of the Empire State Development
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Adelphia and state and local officials had been in negotiations
since January over the telecommunication giant's plans to build a
$100 million operations center in the city's Inner Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Adelphia accepted an incentives package worth more
than $120 million that included $50 million from the state, a $12.4
million ''Jobs Now'' grant from ESD, $7 million from Erie County
for a new parking facility and tax credits and exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was announced by Gov. George Pataki, Mayor Anthony
Masiello, Adelphia owner and chairman John Rigas, his son, Timothy
and a throng of local, state and federal legislators on a balcony
overlooking the future construction site.
</P>
<P>
   ''At least a thousand new jobs right there in what is now a
parking lot,'' said Pataki during his second good-news trip to the
Buffalo area in as many days. On Tuesday, he announced Southwest
Airlines would begin serving Buffalo Niagara International Airport
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-story Adelphia complex will house Adelphia's entire
operations center for its Business Solutions subsidiary and is
expected to contain a hotel, sports theme restaurant, ice hockey
rink, and retail, entertainment and residential space.
</P>
<P>
   The project is the centerpiece of an ambitious larger
redevelopment plan for the Inner Harbor proposed by Adelphia and
two partners. Planners ultimately envision a lively mix of shops,
restaurants, housing, entertainment and a multimillion-dollar water
attraction featuring fountains and a water screen onto which images
could be projected.
</P>
<P>
   The Rigases, who also operate the NHL Buffalo Sabres, would
build the tower next to the Sabres' playing venue, HSBC Arena,
which Adelphia leases from the county and city.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly changing the terms of the current 30-year HSBC lease,
which has 26 years remaining, had come up during talks but the
lease was left unchanged, Adelphia executive vice president Timothy
Rigas said. Losses at the arena have averaged $15 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   ''We, in the end, decided it wasn't worth holding up this
project for the lease concession,'' Rigas said. Instead, it's hoped
the increased development will generate more revenue for the
Sabres, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and legislative leaders in April agreed to include $75
million for Adelphia incentives in the state budget, including $25
to forgive a loan obtained to build the arena.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a difficult situation for me, because this is the
first time I've ever approached the public sector to work out a
financial arrangement,'' John Rigas said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 1,000 jobs being created, the office complex
will house Adelphia's current New York workforce of 500. The
company has also committed to creating another 1,000 jobs in New
York state, including 500 in western New York and 500 in
undisclosed locations. The jobs carry average compensation packages
of about $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the type of investment, this is the type of commitment
that attracts other high-tech businesses,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   The commitment represents a turnaround for Buffalo, long
dependent on a diminishing blue-collar base.
</P>
<P>
   ''This gives Buffalo a new image, a new identity,'' said
Masiello, ''and a new economic base. It shows the rest of the world
that Buffalo can compete for these state-of-the-art jobs ... It
means so much to the new future of our city.''
</P>
<P>
   Groundbreaking is expected next year. Timothy Rigas said
employees would be added gradually and estimated the entire
1,500-member workforce would be operational within four or five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Adelphia, based in Coudersport, Pa., is the nation's
sixth-largest cable television operator, with 5.6 million
customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 0026 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000622.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government officials seek answers in wake of reported bid for Orion Bus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WHITESTOWN, N.Y. (AP) - The parent company of Orion Bus
Industries is exploring a merger, and a financial news service
report says moving operations out of New York state is a
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   A report issued Tuesday by Stark's News Service of Chicago said
that DaimlerChrysler AG had made a bid to acquire Western Star
Trucks Holdings Ltd. to make it an operating unit of its
Oregon-based Freightliner LLC, but the offer had not yet been
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said Freightliner, the market leader in heavy
trucks, was contemplating an eventual shift of Orion's transit bus
assembly to South Carolina if it succeeded in acquiring Western
Star.
</P>
<P>
   Western Star, based in Kelowna, British Columbia, would not
identify the third party or other details of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ''There can be no assurance that any discussions will result in
an agreement or transaction,'' a statement from Western Star said.
''Any proposed transaction would be subject to receipt of all
necessary regulatory and other approvals.''
</P>
<P>
   Orion Bus, which has plants in Whitestown and Rome, does
finishing work on mass-transit buses used by city bus lines
worldwide. It employs more than 700 people at the two sites, and
that fact alone had Mohawk Valley officials, Orion suppliers and
company workers concerned about the local impact of any deal.
</P>
<P>
   Myron Kuchera, president of United Auto Workers Local 2243,
which represents most of the Orion employees locally, said company
officials three weeks ago conducted a ''town hall'' meeting with
local employees and denied the company is for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've been very closed-mouth for months, but we've known
since last spring that this was going on,'' Kuchera said. ''The
bottom line is, if the company decides to move, there is very
little we can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Orion employees at the Whitestown plant said they had heard
rumors about a potential merger. Tim Harrison of Westmoreland, an
employee of Orion for more than seven years, said Freightliner
officials toured the Orion facility a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Armstrong, operations manager at Norbco Inc. of
Westmoreland, an aftermarket parts supplier for Orion, said he
wouldn't be surprised if Orion were bought.
</P>
<P>
   ''They tried to make this thing go,'' Armstrong said. ''They
were ripe for a buyout.''
</P>
<P>
   Orion's business has been booming lately. In December, it was
awarded two contracts worth $125 million from the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority of New York City to provide 125 buses that
run on natural gas and another 125 hybrid diesel-electric buses.
</P>
<P>
   Western Star purchased Orion in 1995, shortly after Orion's work
force had been slashed from 600 to only 65 because of a lack of
orders.
</P>
<P>
   Oneida County Executive Ralph Eannace said his office was
monitoring the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We already have some proposals we've been working on that we
could use to help show any purchaser why they would be well-served
to stay here,'' Eannace said. ''We're just making the outreach (to
DaimlerChrysler) because you have to be proactive in this
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Western Star's statement was made in response to a request from
the Toronto Stock Exchange, which halted trading of Western Star
stock on Tuesday morning because of what Western Star marketing
manager Doug Shand called ''abnormal trading.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The pattern (of trading) did not fit our normal pattern of the
last 12 months. Our shares were up $4.50 on the Toronto Stock
Exchange and up $3 on the American Stock Exchange,'' Shand said.
</P>
<P>
   The American Stock Exchange also halted trading, but trading on
both exchanges resumed Wednesday. By late afternoon, Western Star
was up nearly $1 to just over $19 a share on the Amex.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 0028 </TRAILER>
