<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Population of alewives in Lake Ontario on the rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAPE VINCENT, N.Y. (AP) - Two years after it all but disappeared
from the deep waters of Lake Ontario, the alewife is making a
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary results of a net survey conducted by the U.S.
Geological Survey and the state Department of Environmental
Conservation conducted in late April and May show the alewife, one
of the favorite meals of salmon, chinook and brown trout, at its
most populous level since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''The population is on its way up,'' said Robert O'Gorman, field
station supervisor of the Lake Ontario Biological Station with the
U.S. Geological Survey in Oswego.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers spent more than 16 hours trawling in 13 different
locations at depths ranging from 30 feet to 475 feet to gather
results. Crews conducted about 100 trawlings of 10 minutes each
between Rochester and Cape Vincent, located at the northeastern
corner of the lake.
</P>
<P>
   A similar survey in 1998 had revealed virtually no alewives, the
lowest level since a harsh winter led to a massive die-off of the
fish in 1976-77.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists maintained that the population of the sardine-size
fish was on the verge of collapse because of predators and a lack
of algae, which the alewives eat.
</P>
<P>
   The DEC had cut the number of salmon it stocked in 1993, but
increased it in 1997 after fishing-dependent businesses blamed
lackluster catches on the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   O'Gorman said the largest population of alewives found in the
study was what is referred to by research agencies as the ''1998
year class,'' meaning fish born that year. He said between 66
percent and 75 percent of the fish caught were 2 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was an enormous number of 2-year-old alewives, and quite
a few 1-year-olds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Gorman said water temperatures are the biggest factor in
determining the survival rate of young fish, which are susceptible
to rapid temperature changes. He said the past two mild winters and
early onset of spring weather each year led to favorable
reproductive conditions.
</P>
<P>
   O'Gorman, who said the climate can explain about 60 percent of
the success, expects the results of next year's survey to be even
more positive for the alewife, which can live up to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   However, Brian F. Lantry, an aquatic biologist with the DEC, is
looking more conservatively at the survey results.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to measure it over time, but it does look good,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lantry said the lake's eastern basin between Oswego and the St.
Lawrence River is still a trouble spot for alewives because of the
water clarity there, which is a result of the infestation of
billions of zebra mussels. The alewife's diet includes algae and
plankton, which also is the diet of the voracious mussels.
</P>
<P>
   Lantry said that despite the increase in the alewife population,
the DEC has set its salmon stocking policy through 2002, and there
have been no discussions of stocking more salmon before then.
</P>
<P>
   O'Gorman said the survey also found a large number of lake
trout, which shows the fish is reproducing.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a major milestone in our efforts to restore the
population,'' he said. ''Lake Ontario is the only lake outside Lake
Superior where you can find this naturally producing fish over a
broad area. It's an amazing feat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
