<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bragman says he will add to staff pay from campaign fund  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The ex-majority leader of the state Assembly
said Wednesday he will supplement the legislative salaries of his
remaining staff from his personal campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bragman said he will lose 10 staffers from his North
Syracuse district office on Thursday. The workers he once had as
majority leader are being transferred to the Assembly ''central''
staff controlled by the man Bragman tried to oust, Speaker Sheldon
Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said the five staffers who will remain with him in the
district office will be paid in part from taxpayer money he will
get to run his office. The rest of their salaries will come from
the two campaign funds Bragman accumulated through years of
fund-raising as majority leader. The idea is to keep the staffers'
salaries the same in spite of having his office budget cut from
$1.2 million to $125,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said he has more than $1.2 million in the two funds.
Even a prolonged need to use his campaign money for his office
expenses would not make much of a ''dent'' in the funds, Bragman
said, though he added that he plans to use new contributions and
volunteers to keep his district office adequately staffed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is absolutely proper to supplement the staff,'' Bragman
said Wednesday. ''When they (the Silver forces) are moving out
their computers, we will be moving in ours. We will be providing
every resource that they take out. As far as I'm concerned, this is
a war and it is a war involving the people of this state knowing
what this speaker and the process is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said Assembly personnel on Thursday will take away 11 of
13 computers, fax machines and replace the current phone system in
Bragman's district office with a more basic model.
</P>
<P>
   Silver, a Manhattan Democrat, fired Bragman as majority leader
when Bragman went public with his bid to oust Silver as speaker.
While Bragman said he once had more than enough votes among the
Assembly's Democratic majority to depose Silver, Bragman's support
dissolved under pressure from Silver and his partisans and only 19
Democrats publicly voted against Silver on May 22.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman, who once had three dozen staffers as majority leader,
was reduced to running his office on $125,000 a year or about
$70,000 over the rest of 2000. He also lost his $34,500-a-year
stipend as majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said his district office receives about 250 calls a week
seeking assistance. Constituents should not suffer because he
failed to topple Silver, Bragman said.
</P>
<P>
   Silver spokeswoman Patricia Lynch said Bragman is losing about
$1 million a year in the resources which went with his majority
leader's office.
</P>
<P>
   She said it is ''entirely his choice'' if Bragman wants to pay
staffers out of his campaign funds. When asked if she saw legal or
ethical problems with him doing so, Lynch said, ''it's not mine to
inquire'' about the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said the computers, faxes and other equipment will
eventually end up in the office of the new majority leader. Silver
has said one is unlikely to picked until after November's
legislative elections.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman also said he would talk to the editorial boards of
newspapers around New York to promote the Democratic Majority
Reform Caucus which the dissident Democrats formed during the coup
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels say Silver runs the Assembly in an autocratic manner,
leaving rank-and-file Democrats little say or authority.
</P>
<P>
   Silver has downplayed the extent of his Democrats'
dissatisfaction with his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Silver has appointed ''focus groups'' of Assembly Democrats to
discuss various issues and come up with recommendations to Assembly
Democrats on changing some majority procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said he doubted Silver sincerely wants to open up the
Assembly to meaningful reform. If the focus groups do not amount to
a serious reform effort, Bragman said he would challenge Silver
again after the November elections when Silver must formally be
re-elected to a new term as speaker for the Legislature's 2001-02
session.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am certainly not convinced that the speaker wants to do that
(institute reforms) or is capable of doing that,'' Bragman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
