<DOCNO> APW20000622.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Vote Affects Gun Agreement  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a blow to the landmark agreement between
the nation's largest gun maker and the Clinton administration, the
House voted Wednesday to bar the federal government from helping to
attract more municipalities to the pact.
</P>
<P>
   By a 218-207 vote, the House voted to prevent the government
from spending any money for the Communities for Safer Guns
Coalition. In return for Smith &AMP; Wesson's promise to use gun-safety
devices and sales practices, the 411 localities that have so far
joined the coalition have agreed to make the company's firearms the
preferred gun for their law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, the House muddled its message by voting 219-206
to reject a second provision that would have forbidden the federal
government outright from enforcing the March 17 agreement between
Smith &AMP; Wesson and the federal and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   The two votes underlined the pressure lawmakers are under on the
hot button issue of guns, especially in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Since the successful amendment was added to a massive spending
bill that the administration has already threatened to veto, its
fate is shaky.
</P>
<P>
   ''The gun language is just one more problem on what is already a
very bad bill,'' said Linda Ricci, spokeswoman for the White House
budget office.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the first vote was a clear defeat for the White
House and a slap at Andrew Cuomo, the secretary of the Department
of Housing and Urban Development who has been a leader in forging
the gun agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today's callous action by the House of Representatives strikes
at the heart of HUD's ability to work with local communities to
reduce the awful toll of gun violence,'' he said in a written
statement
</P>
<P>
   He added later, ''The House has now proven that it is firmly in
the hip holster of gun lobby extremists.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Hostettler, R-Ind., who sponsored both amendments,
said in an interview afterward that the two votes were ''overall a
win'' because they sent a message that lawmakers don't want the
Clinton administration pushing communities to purchase Smith &AMP;
Wesson weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ''Local law enforcement agencies won't feel pressure from a
federal agency ... in the procurement of firearms'' as a result of
the first vote, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Walsh, R-N.Y., chief author of the spending bill that
Hostettler's amendments were aimed at, said during the debate that
the measure provided no funds specifically for the gun agreement.
That made the amendments ''unnecessary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hostettler said later that the government often spends money
for activities that are not specified in spending bills, such as
for U.S. troops in Kosovo. With the success of his first amendment,
he said, the Department of Housing and Urban Development would not
be able to issue press releases or have its lawyers help the
coalition of participating communities.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., who led the opposition to
Hostettler's amendments, said the success of his first amendment
was ''absolutely'' a setback.
</P>
<P>
   But she said she hoped the Senate, which has not yet written its
version of the bill, would reject the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Hostettler's language was inserted into a $101 billion measure
financing veterans, housing, environment and space programs for the
coming fiscal year that the House approved by 256-169.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has already threatened to veto the measure
because it would cut some of President Clinton's proposals for
public housing and enforcement of some environmental laws, and
abolish the AmeriCorps national service program.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the gun agreement, Smith &AMP; Wesson agreed to start
installing trigger locks and other gun-safety devices, such as
using ''smart gun'' technology within three years that would allow
only the weapon's owner to use it. In addition, the company agreed
to take such steps as selling guns only after background checks of
the purchaser.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, 411 communities that have so far joined agreed to
make Smith &AMP; Wesson guns the preferred choice for the firearms they
purchase for their law enforcement agencies. They also agreed to
drop the company from lawsuits challenging the gun industry's
safety and marketing practices.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, Hostettler said the Clinton administration
had used the agreement to score political points, and said
communities following it could end up buying inappropriate weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't allow HUD to override officer safety for the purpose of
a political agenda,'' said Hostettler, using the acronym for the
Department of Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the Smith &AMP; Wesson deal accused Hostettler of
helping the National Rifle Association, which has attacked the
agreement. They also said Hostettler's aim was to get even with the
gun maker, which has been sued by other arms companies in federal
court for an alleged restraint of trade conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   ''His objective is very simple,'' said Rep. Richard Neal,
D-Mass., in whose district Smith &AMP; Wesson is based. ''It's to put
Smith &AMP; Wesson out of business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-22-00 0030 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000622.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Teacher Guilty of Killing Cousin  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARABOO, Wis. (AP) -- A former teacher was convicted Wednesday of
killing his cousin, whose dismembered, skinned body washed up in a
river last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Kupaza, 40, was convicted of first-degree intentional
homicide and hiding a corpse in the death of Mwivano Mwambashi
Kupaza, 25, a student from Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Sentencing was scheduled for Friday at 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The victim's arms, head, legs and torso were found in the water
last July near Spring Green. The skin had been removed from most of
the body, including the face.
</P>
<P>
   During closing arguments, Sauk County District Attorney Patricia
Barrett said Kupaza stood to gain financially from her death and
told a series of lies to try to conceal his guilt.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said Peter Kupaza was struggling financially to support
himself and his cousin since his 1998 divorce from Shari Goss. He
was working two jobs and was evicted from two apartments before his
cousin's death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-22-00 0031 </TRAILER>
