<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Who abandoned baby Convicted  </HEADLINE>
By JAMES WEBB
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELVIDERE, Ill. (AP) -- A young woman who admitted she abandoned
her newborn in a neighbor's snowy backyard and kept the secret for
more than three years was convicted Wednesday of involuntary
manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors rejected a first-degree conviction against Kelli Moye,
now 20, despite the prosecution's contention that she knew the
little girl was likely to die when she left her outside hours after
giving birth on Feb. 9, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Moye looked up at the ceiling as Judge Rosemary Collins read the
jury's verdict and breathed deeply. Relatives hugged and wept in
relief. Jim and Sue Moye expressed hope their daughter would be
home soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the jury did a great job and they chose the right
verdict,'' her father said.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of the body, two days after she was left outside,
stunned residents of Poplar Grove, a town of about 750 people
surrounded by farmland 70 miles northwest of Chicago. They named
the baby Angelica Faith and gave her a proper burial, but the
mystery of her birth and death persisted until Moye was arrested
last fall after a fight with Michael Mirshak, the child's father.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Moye didn't tell anyone about the birth -- not
even Mirshak -- because it didn't fit in with her plans to keep him
as her boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Debra Schafer said prosecutors were trying to
put a sinister spin on the actions of a scared teen-ager who
couldn't bring herself to tell her parents and did tell her
boyfriend -- only to be told to get rid of the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ''She felt isolated and alone, and she made a bad choice with
very tragic results,'' Schafer said. ''But that does not
necessarily make her guilty of a criminal offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Moye testified that she placed the infant outside hours after
delivering her in secret as her parents slept at their home and was
too afraid of being caught to check on the child. Mirshak was a
prosecution witness and has not been implicated in the baby's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Moye's parents had contacted police initially after learning
their daughter was the mother of the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a father it was the hardest thing in the world to do, to
turn your daughter in for murder,'' Jim Moye said. ''I kind of
regretted it, but now I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Moye could have faced up to 60 years in prison if convicted of
first-degree murder, but Schafer said she expects a sentence of two
to 10 years for her client.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-22-00 0046 </TRAILER>
