<HEADLINE> Angels 3, Royals 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Jarrod Washburn took a two-hit shutout
into the ninth inning, and Darin Erstad had a home run, three RBIs
and game-saving catch to lead the Anaheim Angels over the Kansas
City Royals 3-1 Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn (3-1) allowed four hits in 8 1-3 innings, struck out
three and walked one. After he gave up a pair of ninth-inning
singles, Troy Percival relieved and allowed an RBI single to Carlos
Beltran.
</P>
<P>
   Jermaine Dye then was robbed of a three-run homer by Erstad, who
leaned against the short fence in the left-field corner and made
the catch as a fan nearly knocked the ball away. Mike Sweeney flied
out, giving Percival his 18th save in 23 chances, just his fifth in
his last nine.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City had averaged seven runs in its previous seven
meetings with the Angels this season.
</P>
<P>
   Mac Suzuki (3-1) allowed all three runs and six hits in seven
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn and Suzuki both had one-hitters through the first 4&AMP;frac12;
innings, until Anaheim's Adam Kennedy -- batting ninth for only the
third time in 65 starts this season -- singled with two outs in the
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad followed with his 14th homer. After two more hits, Suzuki
struck out Tim Salmon with runners at the corners.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy tripled off the center field fence in the seventh for
only his fifth hit in 33 career at-bats against the Royals, and
scored on Erstad's groundout.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Tim Belcher, scheduled Thursday to make his second start
since coming off the disabled list, has an 0-7 career record
against the Royals. Kansas City is the only AL league team the
14-year veteran right-hander has never defeated. Belcher has beaten
every NL team except Arizona and Colorado, the only two he has
never faced. ... Erstad, who has 54 RBIs in 69 games, is trying to
become the first leadoff batter in Angels history with 20 homers
and 100 RBIs. ... Kansas City recalled OF Mark Quinn from Triple-A
Omaha and sent INF Ray Holbert outright to Omaha. ... Washburn's
only other shutout in professional ball was on July 23, 1997, for
Double-A Midland against Shreveport. ... Angels RHP Ken Hill, on
the disabled list since May 10 because of a strained muscle in his
right ribcage, is penciled in to start next Wednesday at Seattle.
... Angels RHP Jason Dickson, sidelined since May 15, was examined
Wednesday by Dr. Lewis Yokum at the Kerlan-Jobe Clinic and had an
MRI that showed additional wear on the right labrum in his
shoulder. Dickson will continue therapy, and no timetable has been
set for him to throw again.
</P>
</TEXT>
