<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinal Egan challenges media to investigate truth  </HEADLINE>
By HADLEY PAWLAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOLTON LANDING, N.Y. (AP) - In his first public appearance as
Roman Catholic archbishop of New York, Edward Michael Egan pledged
to be open and forthcoming with reporters - in most cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to assure you that I want to be as open to you as I
possibly can,'' Egan said at the New York State Broadcasters
Association conference Wednesday night. He urged members of the
media to call him if he violates that promise.
</P>
<P>
   ''I must be willing to cooperate with you openly and honestly if
I expect the same excellence and honesty in your reports,'' Egan
told the broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some things that will remain off limits, said
Egan, 68. Specifically, he won't talk about court cases or pending
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you are before the judge in a court case you are going to
be expected to be silent until the case is resolved,'' Egan said.
</P>
<P>
   Egan, who led the diocese of Bridgeport, Conn., for 12 years,
has refused comment about more than 20 lawsuits pending against
that diocese. In those cases, several people claimed they were
molested by priests when they were altar boys or members of
diocesan youth organizations. The alleged incidents occurred before
Egan was bishop there.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in 42 years in the clergy he has never found the
media to intentionally report falsehoods but, ''unfortunately
misinformation gets out.''
</P>
<P>
   He talked about ''lawyers' shocking fiction,'' hitting the news
pages as truth only to ultimately be exposed as lies. Reputations
can be ruined, Egan said, but when the truth comes out, ''it's on
the back page or before the next commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He really challenged the press tonight,'' said Joseph Reilly,
executive director of the NYSBA. ''Maybe we don't have to be the
first one on the air if we're the rightest one on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan said Americans - and specifically the media - have a
special duty to tell the truth. ''It is essential if our nation is
to be strong and secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan succeeded Cardinal John O'Connor as spiritual leader of 2.4
million Roman Catholics in the New York archdiocese. It is
considered the most prominent Catholic post in America. O'Connor
died of brain cancer May 3 after serving as archbishop for 16
years.
</P>
<P>
   The archdiocese covers Manhattan, Staten Island, the Bronx,
Westchester and surrounding suburban counties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 0050 </TRAILER>
