<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Sought for S. Leone Rebel  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. Security Council and West African
states have agreed on the need to bring Sierra Leone's rebel leader
Foday Sankoh to justice and to investigate illicit diamond sales
that have financed arms purchases by his rebel force.
</P>
<P>
   Britain told Liberia -- identified as the key transit point for
illegal diamond exports and arms shipments to Sankoh's rebels --
that its actions threatened to undermine efforts to restore peace
to Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting took place Wednesday between the council and six
members of the Economic Community of West African States -- Ghana,
Guinea, Liberia, Mali, Nigeria and Togo. They discussed a common
approach to restoring peace, dealing with rebels, diamonds and
arms, and bringing to justice those who have flouted last July's
peace agreement with renewed fighting in May.
</P>
<P>
   ''There isn't 100 percent agreement between ECOWAS and the
Security Council, or even within the Security Council on every
element,'' said British Ambassador Jeremy Greenstock, ''but our
fundamental agendas are the same,''
</P>
<P>
   Britain has formally proposed that the Security Council
institute an embargo on the sale of Sierra Leone diamonds not
authorized by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Greenstock said he told Liberia's Foreign Minister Monie Captan
that his country's current activities ''were potentially and
perhaps actually a major threat to what we're trying to do to put
Sierra Leone together.''
</P>
<P>
   Captan took it ''on the chin,'' Greenstock said. Diplomats added
that the Liberian minister told the council his government was
ready to cooperate with any inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has also proposed expanding the U.N. force in Sierra
Leone from 13,000 to 16,500 as recommended by Secretary-General
Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   ECOWAS Executive Secretary Lansana Kouyate said the
organization's members are prepared to contribute 3,000-3,5000
troops ''provided that we will get sufficient logistics and
financial support.''
</P>
<P>
   Both ECOWAS and the Security Council want those responsible for
breaking the Lome peace agreement that ended Sierra Leone's
eight-year civil war to be brought to justice. But differences
remain on the scope and nature of any war crimes trials.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement broadcast Wednesday on state-run radio, the
Sierra Leone government asked the Security Council to establish a
special war crimes court based in the country but operating under a
blend of national and international law to prosecute Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is backing Sierra Leone and is drafting a
Security Council resolution, but it was unclear if it would be
limited just to Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   Kouyate said the peace agreement gives immunity to Sankoh and
his Revolutionary United Front for previous atrocities, but they
have no immunity from actions since last July. ECOWAS has already
started an investigation on responsibility for recent cease-fire
violations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think ECOWAS have yet reached the point of deciding
what type of procedure they want,'' Greenstock said. ''But it was
clear from them that they want Foday Sankoh tried ... if the
charges are as they look at the moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-22-00 0104 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000622.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Missile Talks Upcoming  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- The United States is set to announce negotiations
with North Korea to stop the development and export of the
communist country's missile technology.
</P>
<P>
   If the talks succeed, shipments to Iran, Pakistan and possibly
other nations could end, thereby easing concerns about a growing
threat to the United States and its friends and allies.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations, due to be announced shortly, follow a decision
by North Korea to extend a moratorium on missile flight tests.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior U.S. official, briefing reporters on a fast-growing
relationship between the United States and the once-secluded and
hostile government in Pyongyang, said Washington still faced a
threat of missile attack by North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, President Clinton will not be deterred in
considering the start of an expensive missile defense program, the
first phase of which is designed with North Korea in mind, said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Also due soon is an announcement of a visit by a high-level
North Korean official to Washington as well as talks to reaffirm
North Korea's pledge to halt a nuclear weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Clinton administration lifted a 50-year embargo
on trade with North Korea, permitting American companies and
individuals to trade with and transfer money to North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea responded Wednesday, extending by nine months its
moratorium on missile tests, according to a Foreign Ministry
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will have a positive effect on Washington high-level
talks,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Phil Reeker said, ''We
welcome the North Korean statement and the continued restraint by
Pyongyang.''
</P>
<P>
   While the two sides also will hold a new round of talks on
terrorism, North Korea remains on the State Department's list of
sponsors of terrorism. Under U.S. law, that prohibits most U.S. aid
and requires Washington to oppose World Bank loans to North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright arrived
Thursday in Beijing for talks with Chinese leaders. She began her
visit by seeing Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan for a luncheon
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   After shaking hands with Tang at the Diaoyutai State Guest
House, Albright said she had ''lots of things to discuss,'' but did
not raise specifics. Reporters were not permitted to sit in on the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Meetings are scheduled later in the day with Vice Premier Qian
Qichen and Premier Zhu Rongji. Albright was scheduled to meet
Chinese President Jiang Zemin Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   She was to fly Friday to Seoul, South Korea, for an update on
the first meeting of the heads of North and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The summit last week in Pyongyang produced an agreement between
South Korea's Kim Dae-jung and North Korea's Kim Jong Il to work
for peace and unity on their bitterly divided peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The North Korean leader held talks in Beijing before the summit.
Albright intends to press the Chinese, who helped set up the
summit, for more information about him, his economic policy and
whether he is committed to peace on the Korean peninsula, a second
senior U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   The moves toward reconciliation between the two Koreas raised
questions bout the continued presence of some 37,000 U.S. troops in
South Korea as a barrier to invasion from the north. Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., the chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, has called on the Clinton administration to begin
considering a pullout.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials and other key members of Congress
said the threat remains and so should the troops, which cost the
United States an estimated $3.2 billion a year to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting China for the first time since March 1999, Albright was
given access to a wide range of top officials, including President
Jiang Zemin, even though the trip was hastily arranged.
</P>
<P>
   She was beginning by seeing Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, with
Vice Premier Qian Qichen and Premier Zhu Rongji scheduled later.
</P>
<P>
   She is bracing for tough questions about a U.S. missile defense,
especially with tensions easing between North and South Korea, said
the U.S. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   China has warned that erecting a missile shield in violation of
a 1972 U.S.-Soviet treaty could touch off a new nuclear weapons
race.
</P>
<P>
   Albright also expects to be quizzed about the talks President
Clinton held in Moscow three weeks ago with Russian President
Vladimir Putin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
