<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Reconstruction a Struggle  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WARREN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA GUAIRA, Venezuela (AP) -- When rain seeps through his family's
tent, Adan Liendo feels helpless.
</P>
<P>
   Six months after mudslides destroyed his home and killed 15,000
people along Venezuela's coast, Liendo and his family still live in
a crowded disaster relief camp. As the rainy season begins, once
again soaking the unstable flanks of nearby Mount Avila, Liendo is
getting desperate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need a place to live -- something better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dec. 15 disaster left 100,000 people homeless. Most found
housing nearby or moved in with relatives, and the government has
moved about 5,500 people to new houses elsewhere in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   But 7,500 still remain in temporary shelters and tents huddled
among blasted-out buildings in the coastal state of Vargas.
Unemployment has soared because businesses were destroyed. Crime is
on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Liendo, 23, lives with his wife and three children in a
12-foot-by-12-foot tent, packed in with 130 others on a former
sports field in La Guaira.
</P>
<P>
   Work crews have cleared the nearby coastal road, but the beach
where fishermen once cast their lines is now covered with
hard-packed, desolate earth. It juts out 200 feet farther than it
once did, onto a churning, brown sea littered with concrete, iron
scraps, refrigerators and other mudslide debris.
</P>
<P>
   Squabbles between President Hugo Chavez's government and the
Vargas state government over control of relief funds have slowed
reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Vargas Gov. Alfredo Laya announced the state had run
out of funding. He said he had no choice but to freeze rebuilding
efforts and fire 5,500 employees -- many of them landslide victims.
</P>
<P>
   State work crews that had begun building wooden homes for Liendo
and other families stopped work, leaving behind piles of lumber.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Laya led 2,000 Vargas residents in a protest in the
capital to demand the federal government hand over $194 million so
the state can continue reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's government defends its efforts, saying it has spent
millions of dollars on clearing buried roads and cleaning river
channels.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I had to start this process again, knowing what I knew six
months ago, I would do everything the same way,'' said Technology
Minister Carlos Genatios, who directs federal reconstruction
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   He said the government has focused on designing a $1.2 billion
reconstruction plan and preparing other communities to accept
Vargas refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Liendo lost his job as a security guard in the
state's layoffs. Bilmania Silva, 44, fears she might also lose her
$150-per-month job at the state comptroller's office.
</P>
<P>
   The insecurity has led to crime, exacerbated by the breakdown of
communities as neighbors and families have scattered.
</P>
<P>
   Silva said no work has begun on two projects her community
desperately needs -- construction of a tunnel to drain water safely
to the sea, and removal of trash left by the mudslides.
</P>
<P>
   Filthy water now runs through an enormous, trash-filled channel
carved out during the flooding near Silva's front porch. As Silva
spoke, her neighbor threw half a mattress by the stream and walked
away.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents have given up and accepted the government's offer
to move away.
</P>
<P>
   Marcos Morales, 35, now lives in the western town of Guarumito,
where on Saturday Chavez inaugurated more than 100 new homes for
mudslide victims.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think I'm going to go back,'' he said. ''The
government has given us very comfortable and dignified homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Vargas, authorities have warned that some areas may
never be habitable again because of the risk of landslides. In
Carmen de Uria, where an estimated 2,000 people are buried in the
rubble, the government has prohibited construction and said it will
build a park to commemorate the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Silva says she knows the danger in Vargas state is real.
</P>
<P>
   ''When it rains, we don't sleep -- we're worried that the river's
going to carry us away,'' she said. But she said she cannot bear to
leave her home state.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been here so many years,'' Silva said. ''I was born here,
and I don't want to leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-22-00 0106 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
