<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Galaxy 1, Fire 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- Greg Vanney scored on a penalty kick
with two minutes to play in regulation as the Los Angeles Galaxy
salvaged a 1-1 tie with the Chicago Fire on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Kevin Terry awarded the Galaxy (7-3-7) the penalty kick
after Jesse Marsch pushed Mauricio Cienfuegos to the ground in the
penalty area.
</P>
<P>
   Fire goalkeeper Zach Thornton dove to the right on the penalty
kick, but Vanney put the shot inside the right post for his fourth
goal of the season, all on penalty kicks.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Wolff put the Fire (9-7-2) ahead in the 75th minute, taking
Diego Gutierrez's pass and shooting just inside the left post for
his fifth goal. Former Galaxy forward Ante Razov also was credited
with an assist.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Armas nearly gave Chicago a 2-0 lead in the 83rd minute,
but Los Angeles forward Cobi Jones, standing on the goal line next
to the left post, cleared Armas' shot.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff had the best scoring opportunity of overtime, capping a
counterattack in the 94th minute with a shot from just inside the
penalty area, which Los Angeles goalkeeper Kevin Hartman dove to
the ground to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago led 16-10 in shots and 7-6 in shots on goal before an
announced crowd of 10,271 at the Rose Bowl. Thornton and Hartman
each made five saves.
</P>
<P>
   The tie continued the Galaxy's slump since the league began to
force the team to divest players May 13 so high-scoring Mexican
forward Luis Hernandez could be added to the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is 2-3-4 after opening the season 5-0-3. Hernandez
has yet to score in six MLS matches and one in the U.S. Open Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
