<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Witnesses: Skakel admitted involvement in murder  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) - Lawyers for Kennedy cousin Michael Skakel
next week will present witnesses to dispute former classmates of
Skakel's who claimed he confessed to killing his teen-age neighbor
in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Two men who attended a residential substance abuse treatment
center with Skakel in the late 1970s testified this week that
Skakel admitted killing 15-year-old Martha Moxley.
</P>
<P>
   Their testimony came during a reasonable cause hearing to
determine whether there is enough evidence to try Skakel and
whether his case will be transferred from juvenile to adult court.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel was 15 at the time of the killing. Now 39, he was
arrested in January after a grand jury consisting of a single judge
found there was probable cause to charge him in the long-dormant
case.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel's attorney, Michael Sherman, told Judge Maureen Dennis
Wednesday that he will call several former students at Elan to
testify about whether Skakel ever made any admissions at the Elan
school in Poland Spring, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm confident that once the judge hears the whole story, she
will have a different picture,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   The defense is expected to begin its case June 28.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Sherman grilled one of the Elan students who
testified for the state.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Coleman testified earlier that Skakel told him he beat
Moxley's skull in with a golf club after she rejected his romantic
advances. He said Skakel told him: ''I'm going to get away with
murder. I'm a Kennedy.'' Skakel's father, Rushton Skakel Sr., is
the brother of Sen. Robert F. Kennedy's widow, Ethel.
</P>
<P>
   During cross-examination, Coleman admitted that he had told the
grand jury that Skakel confessed to him five times, when actually
he only confessed to him twice. Coleman also said that he heard
Skakel admit to the murder during a ''primal scream'' group therapy
session.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman admitted he sometimes has trouble with his ability to
recall.
</P>
<P>
   But he adamantly stood by his testimony that Skakel told him he
killed Moxley.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know what I heard upon initially meeting Michael Skakel ...I
am sure of that - not 99.9 percent but 100 percent,'' Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman also highlighted Coleman's longstanding drug and alcohol
abuse, and ran through Coleman's criminal record, including a 1983
conviction for robbery and a 1999 conviction for trespassing.
Coleman is serving a year in prison on that count.
</P>
<P>
   In other testimony Wednesday, a childhood friend testifying for
prosecutors said that Skakel admitted being at the scene where
Moxley was murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Pugh said Skakel told him years later that he had
masturbated in a pine tree in Moxley's yard the night she was
murdered, Oct. 30, 1975. It was the same pine tree Moxley's
bludgeoned body was found under the next morning, Pugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Pugh said that when they were kids, he and Skakel frequently
climbed an enormous pine tree on the Moxley property, which was
located across the street from the Skakel family estate in Belle
Haven, an exclusive gated community in Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   Pugh said he lost touch with Skakel after Moxley's death.
</P>
<P>
   He said Skakel tried to renew their friendship in the early
1990s, but that he told Skakel he was reluctant because he had some
concerns about Skakel's possible involvement in Moxley's murder.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Pugh said he asked Skakel if he had anything to
do with the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Pugh said Skakel told him he had been in the pine tree
masturbating the night Moxley was killed, ''but that he had nothing
to do with her death.''
</P>
<P>
   That account is similar to what Skakel told a private
investigative firm hired by his family in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with Sutton Associates, Skakel changed the story
he originally gave to police. He originally said he was at his
cousin's house at the time investigators believe Moxley was killed.
But he told Sutton Associates that after he returned home that
night, he climbed a tree outside Moxley's window, threw rocks to
awaken her and masturbated in the tree. He said he ran home when he
heard voices.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman suggested repeatedly that Skakel never told Pugh that
the pine tree they climbed as kids was the same tree Skakel told
him he climbed the night of Moxley's killing.
</P>
<P>
   Pugh acknowledged that he assumed Skakel was referring to the
tree where Moxley's body was found, but he did not come right out
and say it was the same tree.
</P>
<P>
   Pugh said Skakel had ''an attraction, an infatuation'' with
Moxley.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also called Judith Kallen, from the state Department
Children and Families, who said the juvenile system does not have
any facilities to treat, hold or rehabilitate someone after they
reach the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law in effect in 1975, Skakel could face a maximum of
four years if he is convicted as a juvenile. If he is convicted as
an adult, he could get 25 years to life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 0126 </TRAILER>
