<HEADLINE> Circuit on a silicon chip mimics wiring of the brain  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW FORDAHL
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists have developed an electronic circuit that mimics the
wiring of the human brain in some ways - an achievement that could
revolutionize computer science and improve understanding of how
nature's most powerful processor works.
</P>
<P>
   The circuit, built on a silicon chip the size of a fingernail,
is far from the thinking machines of science fiction. For one
thing, it cannot learn the way the brain can.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers say it could result in better speech and object
recognition by computers.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a demonstration of what's possible when circuits
compute in biological ways,'' said Rahul Sarpeshkar, a computer
science professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology who
worked on the project. ''We're still far away from building a
brain.''
</P>
<P>
   The findings were published in Thursday's issue of the journal
Nature.
</P>
<P>
   The project is the culmination of more than two decades of work
using transistors and silicon to mimic the natural circuitry in the
brain. It is the first time a circuit inspired by the brain's
cortex has been created in hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional circuits work in one of two ways: They are either
digital and specific such as computer processors, or analog and
nonspecific like radio amplifiers. Research suggests the brain is
able to do digital and analog computing at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Someone watching a highway, for instance, can sort distinct
objects like a police cruiser and perceive changes in direction,
speed and color. Traditional digital circuits in computers aren't
nearly as efficient as the brain in perceptual tasks.
</P>
<P>
   The latest research, done at Lucent Technologies' Bell Labs in
New Jersey, combines both digital and analog processing by using
artificial neurons that either excite or inhibit each other based
on responses, or feedback, from other neurons.
</P>
<P>
   ''In one simultaneous circuit, both digital selection and analog
amplification can co-exist,'' Sarpeshkar said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers applied simultaneous electrical currents to two
artificial neurons in their circuit. It selected the stronger of
the stimuli and suppressed its response to the weaker. That is not
unlike, say, a frog choosing which of two flies to eat, the
researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   And the circuit, like a brain, maintained its selection as the
weaker current was increased and the stronger decreased.
</P>
<P>
   Another unique aspect of the circuit is no single element made
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you take a Pentium chip and cut a single wire, then it
would probably stop functioning,'' said Richard Hahnloser, another
MIT researcher. ''If you took our circuit, you could cut a wire and
it would still work the same.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be at least 50 years before artificial neural circuitry
approaches the abilities of the brain and its 240 billion neurons,
Sarpeshkar said.
</P>
<P>
   But even simple circuits are useful in demonstrating how
biological networks operate, said Dean Buonomano, a neurobiology
professor at the University of California at Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Nature: http://www.nature.com
</P>
<P>
   Bell Labs: http://www.bell-labs.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 0220 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000622.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gores, Venturas Bond in Minn.  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE GLOVER
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- The Gores and the Venturas raised some
eyebrows with quality bonding time, munching popcorn, giggling and
cheering as Ventura's daughter put her horse through its paces in a
cavernous arena.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've hit it off,'' said Gore spokesman Chris Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, generally accused of being wooden and
stiff, and Minnesota's flamboyant Gov. Jesse Ventura, never accused
of either, are spending more than a day together in a pairing that
includes wives Tipper and Terry.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're good friends, it's not complicated,'' said Gore, the
Democratic presidential contender.
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, very complicated.
</P>
<P>
   The four hooked up Wednesday at the governor's mansion and then
headed to a very large -- and mostly empty -- arena where about 100
people watched a group of riders put their sleekly groomed horses
through their paces.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were kept across the hall, but the couples were
clearly having a ball. They chatted constantly with animated
gestures. Gore wore his trademark cowboy boots, while Ventura
donned a baseball cap. There was no thought given to ties.
</P>
<P>
   Their big moment came when the Venturas' daughter, 16-year-old
Jade Janos, trotted into the arena on her horse -- Jardiniere --
wearing a very formal long gold coat and brown tights, sitting
stiffly in the saddle with a bowler hat on her head.
</P>
<P>
   Her name, by the way, is Janos because Ventura's real name is
James Janos, changed during his professional wrestling career. She
was the focus for the evening, but most were paying attention to
the growing relationship between Gore and Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   The pairing is raising some eyebrows. Ventura was elected as a
Reform Party candidate, and was that party's top elected official
until he quit and became an independent.
</P>
<P>
   He's demonstrated some appeal with independent voters, and some
argued that an association with Ventura's offbeat image could make
Gore seem less stiff. Aides said it was simply a case of chemistry
-- and some shared issues.
</P>
<P>
   He and Gore met earlier this year for breakfast, followed by a
dinner and gathering where the wives hit it off as well, Lehane
said. The Gores were staying the governor's mansion and spending
some quality time together in private before a public session
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The wives went for a private ride of their own earlier
Wednesday, and all four shared an intimate dinner at the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   The meal opened with cranberry apple breaded walleye, followed
by rack of lamb and finished off with sour cream cheesecake. Green
beans and mushrooms, along with a potato dish, accompanied the main
course in a very Midwestern meal.
</P>
<P>
   The formal horse show was the highlight of Wednesday's events,
but there was a very real purpose behind the event.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura spokesman David Ruth said daughter Jade was born with
epileptic seizures, which caused neurological damage. She has a
learning disability and is in a special education program.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents are big equestrians, owning the Jesters' Falling
Tree Ranch, and Ruth said Jade is an enthusiastic rider. ''It's
something she excels at and it's helpful to her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Ventura head to a junior high school in suburban
Minnetonka on Thursday for a daylong event focusing on special
education needs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's association with Ventura has not been lost on local
Democrats as Gore continued his focus on Midwestern battleground
states. On his way to a meeting with Ventura, Gore stopped to chat
with picketers on strike against a hotel and huddled privately with
Democratic activists at a St. Paul restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd gathered outside the restaurant, including about a dozen
people carrying signs backing Republican presidential rival Texas
Gov. George W. Bush and one saying ''Gore-Ventura 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Borovansky waited outside with some advice for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's see some personality, it's been boring so far,''
Borovansky said he would tell Gore.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore actually shook his hand, the tune had changed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just be yourself and you'll be great,'' he told Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
