<HEADLINE> Dow Dips 32; Nasdaq Drops 24  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened modestly lower Thursday as
technology shares gave back some gains following a big runup this
week.
</P>
<P>
   In the early going on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 31.82 at 10,465.92, and the Nasdaq composite index
was down 23.65 at 4,040.36.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Thursday's trading, the Nasdaq index had climbed
for five straight sessions and had nearly returned to where it
began the year. At its low point on May 23, the Nasdaq was down
28.6 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Micron Technology slipped $3.125 to $87.75 as traders
worried that the chip maker's earnings, due out later in the day,
might not be as strong as hoped for. Mobile phone maker Nokia also
lost ground, slipping $2.50 to $58.125.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which led the market higher Wednesday, reversed an
earlier slide from the morning and was up 68.7 cents at $81.375.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was off 9.40 at 1,469.73, and
the Russell 2000 index up 0.33 at 527.94.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones by a 7-to-5 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 128.24 million
shares after 30 minutes of trading, up slightly from 125.99 million
shares the same time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.6 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.5 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.3 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.2 percent.
</P>
