<DOCNO> APW20000622.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writer, Journalist Droit Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Michel Droit, a prize-winning French novelist,
journalist and one of 40 members of the prestigious Academie
Francaise, died Thursday, the Academie announced. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   Droit died in La Celle-Saint-Cloud, outside Paris, the Academie
said. No cause of death was given.
</P>
<P>
   A novelist, essayist and editorialist for two decades with the
conservative daily Le Figaro, Droit gained wide acclaim for his
interviews with Gen. Charles de Gaulle.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, he was elected to the Academie Francaise -- one of only
40 ''immortals'' as the institution's members are known -- to fill
the vacancy left by Joseph Kessel.
</P>
<P>
   Droit was born in Vincennes, outside Paris, on Jan. 23, 1923,
and began his journalism career at 21, as a correspondent covering
the French Army in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He later worked for radio and television, and was the only
journalist in France to interview de Gaulle on television -- in
December 1965, June 1968 and April 1969, a year before the
general's death in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Droit's professional career was intricately linked to de
Gaulle's. In 1972, Droit won the Edmond-Michelet prize for ''A Free
Frenchman,'' a documentary about de Gaulle, France's most
influential postwar leader.
</P>
<P>
   His five-volume ''Man of Destiny'' is widely regarded as one of
the most thorough examinations of de Gaulle's life and work.
</P>
<P>
   Editor in chief at France's state-run television in the early
1960s, Droit launched several successful programs, including ''A
Propos,'' which ran for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Droit worked at Le Figaro's literary supplement from 1961-71,
and went on to write columns for the weekly Figaro Magazine. In
1984, he publishing four volumes of his private diary, and later,
two volumes of memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   He was married and had two children. Funeral arrangements were
pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
