<HEADLINE> Aeroflot Protests U.S. Smoking Ban  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's largest air carrier has accused the
United States of breaking international law by banning smoking on
all scheduled airline flights between the United States and other
countries, the company said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Aeroflot appealed to the International Air Transport Association
this week, asking it to decide whether the ban, which went into
effect June 4, was legal.
</P>
<P>
   ''By introducing the new regulation, the United States has
extended its law to foreign legal entities beyond its territory,
which blatantly contradicts the norms of international law,''
Aeroflot said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Many Russian smokers used to choose Aeroflot for long-distance
flights because it allowed smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking is widespread in Russia, and is allowed in most public
places.
</P>
</TEXT>
