<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 60; Nasdaq Slides 36  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks edged lower Thursday as traders took
profits from a runup in technology shares.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 60.11 points at 10,437.63, and the Nasdaq
composite index was down 35.92 at 4,028.09.
</P>
<P>
   Tech shares giving up ground included Micron Technology, which
fell $3.813 to $86.938 as traders worried that the chip maker's
earnings, due out later in the day, might not be as strong as hoped
for.
</P>
<P>
   Mobile phone maker Nokia also lost ground, slipping $4.375 to
$56.625, and rival Ericsson also fell $1.688 to $20.563.
</P>
<P>
   Other tech bellwethers that have been on the upswing in recent
days also gave back some ground, including Intel, off $1.75 at
$137.25, and International Business Machines, down $1.50 to $113.
Yahoo! fell $5.563 to $137.25 after an analyst expressed concerns
about the outlook for online advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which led the market higher Wednesday, reversed an
earlier slide from the morning and was up 43.8 cents at $81.125.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Thursday's trading, the Nasdaq index had climbed
for five straight sessions, nearly returning to where it began the
year. At its low point on May 23, the Nasdaq was down 28.6 percent
since the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Traders were also looking ahead to the Federal Reserve's regular
meeting next Tuesday and Wednesday. There have been signals that
the economy has been slowing in response to the Fed's series of
interest rate increases, but investors are still bracing for the
possibility that the Fed may tighten credit further to keep
inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're seeing some profit taking,'' said Tom Galvin, chief
equity straegist at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities. ''I
think we're digesting the gains of the Nasdaq over the past four
weeks and looking ahead to the Fed meeting and the likelihood of
several earnings confessions next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Traders said there was little effect from a rumor, quickly
denied by the Fed, that the central bank's chairman, Alan
Greenspan, was in an auto accident.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was off 15.90 at 1,463.23, and
the Russell 2000 index off 1.60 at 526.01.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones by a 8-to-5 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 446.24 million
shares at midday, down slightly from 460.54 million shares the same
time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
