<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Salvages Coalition Government  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN LAUB
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister Ehud Barak salvaged his shaky
government Thursday with a last-minute political maneuver and won
assurances from a rebellious party that it would not challenge him
again, at least while he tries to negotiate a peace treaty with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   However, Barak's diverse six-party alliance may not hold
together long enough to get such a historic accord approved by
Israel's parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In defusing this week's political crisis, which was replete with
threats, ultimatums and all-night negotiations, Barak survived the
worst threat to his government during his one-year rule.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly relieved, a beaming prime minister addressed loyalists
of his One Israel party after he got word that the religious Shas
party had withdrawn its resignation 20 minutes before it was to
have taken effect Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Barak appealed to all parties to set aside their squabbling.
''We cannot let the rage take over,'' he said, referring to the
bitter feuding between Shas and its nemesis, the secular Meretz
party, that had nearly torn apart the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's political drama had raised questions about a renewed
U.S. effort to mediate between Israel and the Palestinians. Had
Barak lost his parliamentary majority Thursday, there would have
been little reason for Washington to press on.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's Mideast envoy, Dennis Ross, arrived in
Jerusalem and was to hold talks with Barak later Thursday. Next
week, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will join Ross to
assess prospects for convening a Mideast summit in Washington that
Clinton would play host.
</P>
<P>
   In such a summit, Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
would try to reach final agreement on the terms of Palestinian
statehood. A treaty is due in September, and negotiators have made
little progress in solving their disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Israel wants a summit soon. However, Palestinian negotiator Saeb
Erekat said Thursday there was no point in convening a top-level
gathering until Israel has honored its outstanding commitments,
including an additional West Bank troop withdrawal. The
Palestinians expect Ross to bring with him U.S. guarantees that the
pullback, initially due Friday, will be carried out within two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Shas, meanwhile, signaled that it would not try to sabotage
Barak's peace moves, for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   ''Barak can go to the United States in the near future ... for
the continuation of the peace process,'' Shas leader Eli Ishai
said, referring to a possible summit. ''But we haven't committed to
the results of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Shas' founder, Rabbi Ovadia Yosef, is a political moderate, but
the party's supporters are overwhelmingly hawkish. Throughout the
years, Shas has zigzagged on land-for-peace issues, fearful of
losing popular support.
</P>
<P>
   A peace treaty needs to win an absolute majority of 61
legislators in the 120-seat parliament before passing yet another
hurdle -- a national referendum. Shas, with its 17 legislators, is
seen by Barak as crucial to obtaining the necessary votes.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition crisis was triggered by a dispute that had nothing
to do with Mideast peacemaking. Shas sought more state funds for
its bankrupt private school system and balked at demands by Meretz
leader Yossi Sarid, the education minister, to control the flow of
the money.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the immediate argument, Shas and Meretz have been bitter
enemies for years, reflecting the deep divides in Israeli society.
Shas represents low-income, religiously observant Israelis with
Middle Eastern roots. Meretz is the party of choice for well-to-do,
dovish Israelis from a European background.
</P>
<P>
   Shas has denounced Sarid as an arrogant racist, while the Meretz
leader has accused Shas of trying to extort money from the state.
</P>
<P>
   Meretz, which has made a peace treaty with the Palestinians a
top priority, reluctantly paved the way for Shas' return to the
government when Meretz' three Cabinet ministers resigned late
Wednesday. Meretz will remain a partner in the coalition, and said
it would loyally support Barak in his peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting that Barak forced the resignations on Meretz, Sarid
said ''there were a lot of strong hints'' that this was the only
option.
</P>
<P>
   Barak thanked Meretz, saying that ''there are few precedents for
such a sacrifice for the common good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
