<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Plane Crash Kills 42  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A Chinese domestic airliner flying in stormy
weather was struck by lightning and crashed Thursday in central
China, killing all 42 people aboard, state media and officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Wuhan Airline's flight, carrying 38 passengers and four
crew, came down at 3 p.m. in a rural suburb of Wuhan, an industrial
center and capital of Hubei province.
</P>
<P>
   ''We lost contact'' with the plane, said an official at Wuhan's
Wangjiadun Airport, who refused to give her name.
</P>
<P>
   The state-run Xinhua News Agency said the plane, a domestically
made YUN-7, was descending for landing when lightning struck and
the aircraft exploded. It said all 42 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was raining very hard,'' said a government official in
nearby Yongfeng township. ''The weather was very bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodies, bits of wreckage and debris from passengers' luggage
fell on the banks of the Han River and nearby dikes, Xinhua said.
It quoted witnesses as saying the falling debris upset a dredging
boat in the river and that several people were missing.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether any people on the ground were hurt or
confirmed killed.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the plane plunged into a farmer's house, a local
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Photos from Xinhua showed the plane's tail sinking into the
river. Rescuers pulled at part of the plane on a dike in Shitai
village, 12 to 18 miles from Wuhan.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators found one of the plane's two flight data recorders
and were searching for the other, Xinhua said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, which seated 54, was flying from Hubei's Enshi county
to Wuhan, Xinhua said.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen of the passengers were from Enshi, with the others
coming from Wuhan, Beijing and other parts of China, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday night, more than 30 relatives gathered at a nearby
hotel, waiting for word of whether the bodies had been retrieved,
Xinhua said.
</P>
<P>
   Wuhan Airlines immediately grounded the three other YUN-7s in
its fleet as part of its investigation, Xinhua reported.
</P>
<P>
   The YUN-7 is reputed to be among the most reliable of China's
few domestically made planes. State-run Xi'an Aircraft Corporation
began manufacturing the YUN-7 in 1986, offering passenger and cargo
models. There are currently 132 YUN-7 being used in China,
according to recent state media reports.
</P>
<P>
   The accident was the first major airplane crash in China since a
Korean Air cargo slammed into a Shanghai construction site 14
months ago, killing the three-member crew and six people on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Two months earlier, in February 1999, a China Southwest Airlines
passenger plane crashed in a field 250 miles south of Shanghai in
China's coastal Zhejiang province. All 61 people aboard the
Russian-built TU-154 were killed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
