<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Health Plan Revamp Urged  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Effectively combating fraud, improving
purchases of prescription drugs and other steps could save millions
of dollars for the government's health care program for the
military, a congressional auditor told lawmakers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Opportunities exist to save potentially hundreds of millions
of dollars that could be used to purchase care for military
beneficiaries,'' Stephen Backhus, director of veterans' affairs and
military health care issues for the General Accounting Office, told
a House Budget Committee task force.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department's managed health care plan, known as
TRICARE, provides health care to active-duty personnel as well as
dependents and military retirees.
</P>
<P>
   The program spends about $225 million a year just processing
claims, a cost that has drawn criticism from many in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is critical that Congress do all it can to help the federal
government keep its commitment to military retirees and their
families,'' said Rep. Mac Thornberry, R-Texas, and chairman of the
task force on defense and international relations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fixing the administrative inefficiencies in the current health
care system'' is one way to achieve that goal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The national average cost to process a Medicare claim last year
was $1.78 compared with $7.50 for a claim under the TRICARE
program, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Government and private sector officials cautioned that it is
difficult to compare the two programs. Medicare is a
fee-for-service program while TRICARE is a managed care program
with a complex system of authorizations, referrals and provider
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Also, TRICARE represents a small amount of a provider's income,
leaving little incentive for doctors to upgrade their networks to
file claims electronically, officials said. Electronic claims would
significantly cut costs for the program.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Backhus and other auditors outlined some possible ways to
save money:
</P>
<P>
   --An effective anti-fraud program could recover the estimated
$290 million to $580 million lost to fraud annually.
</P>
<P>
   --The Defense Department and Veterans Administration could join
in buying pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   --Reforming TRICARE operations such as mailroom handling and
document preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
http://www.house.gov/budget/hearings/taskforce--defense.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
