<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Pitch Plan To Help Poor  </HEADLINE>
By CAREN BENJAMIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bipartisan group of senators Thursday
introduced their version of a plan to offer tax breaks and savings
incentives to neighborhoods left behind by the decade's prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The plan mirrors one supported by President Clinton and House
Republicans but adds several elements, including a program to
encourage poor people to save money.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Clinton and House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.,
jointly announced a multibillion-dollar package of tax breaks and
other benefits to attract investments and jobs to poor areas.
</P>
<P>
   But the new plan ''is one step further and a more aggressive
approach than what the House and the president have offered,'' said
Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Penn.
</P>
<P>
   So far the bill is backed by three Senate Republicans including
Santorum and four Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''While welfare reform has had a dramatic affect on some
individuals, communities were left behind,'' Santorum said.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of both the House measure and what's likely to
become the Senate's bill are incentives like low-income housing tax
credits aimed at specific, impoverished neighborhoods and rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
   These tracts would be specified as either empowerment zones or
renewal communities and granted -- depending their designation --
somewhat different tax incentives and other perks aimed at spurring
job growth.
</P>
<P>
   Empowerment zones were enacted in 1993 but have never been fully
funded.
</P>
<P>
   Renewal communities are the House Republican's version of those
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Both plans add empowerment zones around the country. The
Senate's plan also ''beefs them up'' by fully funding the projects,
Santorum said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference between the House bill and the senators'
is the inclusion of incentives for banks to provide individual
development accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In the senators' proposal banks would match dollar-for-dollar
the money low-income people put into one of these accounts. To
encourage banks to participate, the government would offer the
banks a tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   Money in these accounts could be spent only to pay for
education, start a small business or buy a home.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reality is that success in today's new economy is defined
less and less by how much you earn and more and more by how much
you own. This is all about expanding the winner's circle,''
Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who offered a similar proposal in his State of the
Union address, has backed the bank plan, Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   The senators' bill also expands the role of religious
organizations in federally funded community programs. Under
Clinton's plan, faith-based groups can run federally funded drug
and alcohol programs. The Senate bill would expand their role to
other charitable causes.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plan would cost an estimated $12 billion over five
years -- as much as $7 billion more than the White House proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the additional money is to cover the savings program,
Lieberman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-22-00 1527 </TRAILER>
