<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Eyes Partial Congo Pullout  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- Ten days after Rwandan forces handed it
an embarrassing military setback in northern Congo, Uganda said
Thursday it was withdrawing five battalions from the divided
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential spokeswoman Hope Kivengere said U.N. observers were
supervising the withdrawal of Ugandan troops around the Congo River
port of Kisangani, where hundreds were killed in fighting between
Rwandan and Ugandan forces this month.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda sent thousands of forces to Africa's
third-largest nation in support of rival rebel forces opposed to
Congolese President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   At least 518 people, including 319 Congolese civilians, were
killed in the weeklong fighting in Kisangani, the International
Committee of the Red Cross said.
</P>
<P>
   In her statement, Kivengere did not mention the fighting, saying
the Ugandan pullout was ''part of the United Nations
demilitarization plan for that zone.''
</P>
<P>
   James Wapakabulo, a top official in Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni's National Resistance Movement, said the pullout was made
possible by the U.N. presence and would be completed within two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Uganda's involvement in the Congo's civil war has grown
unpopular, and Kivengeri's announcement came one week before
Ugandans vote whether to keep the Museveni-backed ''no-party''
system or return to multiparty politics.
</P>
<P>
   It also came one day after Uganda's Parliament passed a
resolution urging the government to heed a regional peace deal and
withdraw Ugandan troops from Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also approved resolution requiring monthly briefings
from the government on its progress in implementing the accord, the
government-owned New Vision reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The accord was signed in July and August in Lusaka, Zambia, by
Congo and its backers, Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia, as well as by
Uganda and Rwanda and their rebel allies.
</P>
<P>
   Under the pact, 5,537 U.N. observers are to be stationed in
Congo to supervise a cease-fire and the withdrawal of foreign
forces. So far, only 100 U.N. personnel have been deployed.
</P>
<P>
   During Wednesday's debate, legislators also asked the U.N. and
the international community to honor their obligations spelled out
in the Lusaka accord, the New Vision reported.
</P>
<P>
   However, it rejected a draft resolution urging the government to
utilize all official channels to promote a peaceful relationship
with Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Already, U.N. officials have worried that the proxy war may
again erupt between the two rebel factions, each backed by Rwanda
and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   The Ugandan-backed Congolese Liberation Movement, which has
fought alongside the Ugandan army in Kisangani, has said it would
base itself in the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
