<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Keeps Plane Contract Plan  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon announced Thursday it will stick
to its winner-take-all approach in awarding the largest weapon
contract in history -- $200 billion to build a next-generation
fighter plane -- to either Boeing Co. or Lockheed Martin Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon had been studying the possibility of altering its
approach so that both the winner and loser would have a hand in
producing the aircraft, known as the Joint Strike Fighter. Some
analysts believe the loser essentially may be finished as a fighter
aircraft manufacturer because there is no other new fighter on the
drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   Both Seattle-based Boeing and Lockheed Martin, based in
Bethesda, Md., have built prototypes of their aircraft and soon
will begin flying them. If the current schedule holds, the winner
of the design competition will be announced in the spring, when a
new administration is in place.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Pentagon's approach, the winner of the design
competition will build all the planes. An alternative was to have
the winner and loser share in the manufacturing, on the theory this
would keep both in business and would mitigate against a sole
producer inflating its production costs.
</P>
<P>
   The winner-take-all approach ''seems to make the most sense to
us,'' Jacques Gansler, the Pentagon's technology chief, said at a
news conference. He announced that Defense Secretary William Cohen
had written Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., explaining the importance
and future direction of the project.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to Lewis, chairman of the House Appropriations
subcommittee on defense, Cohen sounded less explicit than Gansler
about the Pentagon's intentions on the question of maintaining
competition in Joint Strike Fighter production. Cohen noted that
the Pentagon has considered a number of options, all based on a
single aircraft design. One option is for the winner to share
production with the loser.
</P>
<P>
   ''Each option we have studied offers potential benefits and
drawbacks, both tangible and intangible,'' Cohen wrote. ''We will
continue to evaluate these options and to develop a comprehensive
assessment that our successors can use as they make decisions on
the future course of the JSF program.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said he asked the Rand Corp., a think tank associated with
the Defense Department, to review options and to report back by
Dec. 1. Gansler said the Rand study will be an ''independent
assessment'' of whether to stick to the winner-take-all approach --
''to make sure we're doing the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Pentagon plans to issue a formal
solicitation for industry proposals for JSF design in September,
Gansler said.
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Strike Fighter is intended to provide the Air Force a
replacement for its current fleet of F-16 fighters, as well as
replacements for the Marine Corps' AV-8B Harrier jets and Navy and
Marine Corps F/A-18s. At least 3,000 aircraft are to be built, at
an average projected cost of $30-$35 million apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Some in Congress recently have questioned the direction of the
program and have proposed cutting its funds.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to Lewis, Cohen called the Joint Strike Fighter
critically important to the modernization of the U.S. military and
''the cornerstone of tactical aircraft modernization.'' He said it
was the ''only affordable solution'' to the problem of maintaining
superior warplanes through the first half of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Joint Strike Fight site: http://www.jast.mil
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
