<HEADLINE> Objections Raised Over War Memorial  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- A group of 707 Japanese-Americans asked Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt on Thursday to eliminate a disputed
Japanese-American creed to be carved on a World War II memorial
under construction near the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   A petition was presented to John Parsons, associate regional
director of the National Park Service, which has approved the
monument. Sponsors of the petition said he promised to brief
Babbitt and then issue a response.
</P>
<P>
   The group said it would agree to eliminate all names and
quotations from the monument.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand that concerns have been raised,'' said Cherry
Tsutsumida, executive secretary of the National Japanese American
Memorial Foundation, ''but these are issues that have been raised
repeatedly with the board and an overwhelming group has approved
the memorial.''
</P>
<P>
   The monument, due to be dedicated in November, commemorates both
Japanese-Americans who served in U.S. forces and more than 100,000
civilians from the west coast who were interned in camps during the
war.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are significant areas of concern about the
inscriptions,'' the petition said, ''including inaccuracies,
misrepresentations, gender biases, and exclusion of diverse
perspectives.''
</P>
<P>
   The group particularly objected to the creed written by the late
Mike Matsuoka, whom it identified as field secretary of the
Japanese-American Citizens League (JACL) during the war.
</P>
<P>
   ''He and JACL strongly advocated 'constructive cooperation' with
the U.S. government, even if it meant massive violations of human,
civil and constitutional rights,'' the petition said.
</P>
<P>
   The internment, approved by the Supreme Court as a war measure,
has since been repudiated by successive presidents. Congress has
voted compensation to the internees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
