<HEADLINE> 'Harry Potter' Creator Honored  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland (AP) -- J.K. Rowling, creator of the
magical world of Harry Potter, received an honorary doctorate
Thursday for helping millions of children discover ''the pure joy
of reading.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Jo Rowling has shown that children's books are still capable
of capturing and enchanting an immense audience, irrespective of
the competing attractions of television, Nintendo, Gameboy and
Pokemon,'' said spokeswoman Sue Cunningham of the University of St.
Andrews, Scotland's oldest university.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling's three books about Harry Potter and his classmates at
Hogwarts school of wizardry have sold more than 37 million copies
worldwide. She was also recently named an Officer of the Order of
British Empire.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth Harry Potter book is due out July 8; its title and
contents have been kept secret. A movie is to start filming this
year.
</P>
