<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Lott See July China Vote  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Both President Clinton and Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott expressed optimism Thursday that the Senate would
vote on granting permanent normal trade relations to China next
month.
</P>
<P>
   But a possible amendment by Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., setting
up a procedure for U.S. sanctions against China for weapons
proliferation, could frustrate meeting such a timetable.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the China trade bill are hoping to keep further
amendments off the landmark legislation so it does not have to go
back to the House for another vote.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike most amendments proposed so far, which have little
apparent support, Thompson's measure has significant backing among
Senate conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Clinton administration and Republican supporters of
the China trade bill have been unable to persuade Thompson not to
press his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has said he wants a separate Senate vote on his
legislation at about the same time the China trade bill is debated
-- or he'll press it as an amendment.
</P>
<P>
   That has prompted others with amendments to demand that they,
too, get separate votes. It's causing a potential procedural
nightmare for Senate leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson announced on Thursday he had signed up two new
co-sponsors for his bill -- Lott and Sen. Conrad Burns, R-Mont. --
bringing the number of sponsors to 15.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's signing on was not viewed as an encouraging sign by China
trade bill advocates.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott told reporters on Thursday, ''There are a lot of us
that are concerned about Chinese nuclear weapon proliferation (and
who) are not going to be inclined to vote against an amendment
dealing with the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lott said, ''It is clearly my intent to call it up before
the August recess,'' although adding, ''It might not be as easy
done as said.''
</P>
<P>
   In a Senate speech, Thompson said that China over the past
several years had assisted missile programs in North Korea, Libya,
Iran and possibly Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot turn a blind eye to these factors as we consider
(China trade),'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton told reporters that he and Lott had
talked earlier in the week by phone and ''I believe we have an
agreement'' for a vote in July.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously I wish we could have voted on it before the 4th of
July recess,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I met with a group of senators (Wednesday), a bipartisan
group, and will continue to work it hard. But I think we're on
schedule now for a timely vote,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which passed the House in May after over fierce
objections by organized labor, would end annual congressional
reviews of China's trade status and grant it the same permanent
benefits that nearly all other U.S. trading partners receive.
</P>
<P>
   It would also permit U.S. companies to take full advantage of
the market-opening steps taken by China as part of its upcoming
entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The China trade bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House: http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO: http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-22-00 1708 </TRAILER>
