<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hastert Presents Whistle Compromise  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The toot of a train whistle isn't quaint to
folks in the Chicago suburbs, who have rallied House Speaker Dennis
Hastert and other lawmakers to fight a pending federal requirement
that trains blow their horns day and night at certain railroad
crossings.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of Congress gave Federal Railroad Administration
chief Jolene Molitoris a bipartisan plan that seeks to address
citizens' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ''There needs to be a common-sense approach, so that we can
guarantee a reliability of safety and not have continuous
whistle-blowing,'' Hastert said after Thursday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The FRA's proposal, required by Congress in a 1994 law, would
most affect 2,058 railroad crossings across America where
whistle-blowing now is banned.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, 899 are in Illinois, the vast majority in towns
ringing Chicago. Wisconsin has 204, followed by Minnesota, Indiana
and Virginia, according to the FRA.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would supersede local ''whistle bans'' requiring
all trains to blow their horns when they approach crossings that do
not have state-of-the-art safety devices.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to keep impatient drivers off the tracks. An FRA
analysis concluded crossings with conventional gates but no
whistles have 62 percent more accidents than those where horns are
blown.
</P>
<P>
   The Illinois delegation, led by Hastert and Rep. Bill Lipiniski,
a Democrat, wants whistle bans to be allowed at intersections with
lights that have had no more than two accidents in five years, or
for those accident-free for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Crossings that do not meet those criteria would have 10 years,
instead of the two years currently in the proposed regulation, to
upgrade their safety devices.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also would give stronger consideration to
lower-cost alternatives, such as increased law enforcement or a
public awareness campaign, to allow a whistle ban to continue.
</P>
<P>
   FRA spokesman Warren Flatau declined to discuss the lawmakers'
plan but suggested there is room for compromise before the rule is
finalized by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's possible that there are going to be revisions (to the
rule) reflecting all the comments we've received,'' Flatau said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers' involvement follows an outpouring of angry
reaction to the proposal from Illinoisans and others around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve well-attended public hearings were held -- four in the
Chicago area. During the public comment period, which ended May 26,
an unusually large number of people sent letters to the FRA; by
Thursday, 2,734 were posted to the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   They came from individuals, politicians, local officials and
businesses with concerns ranging from worries about plummeting home
values to distrust the proposal would do any good to fears about
how to pay for silencing the whistles.
</P>
<P>
   ''You would have to experience those blasts to realize how
nerve-racking it is,'' wrote Leroy Mally of Oak Lawn, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ''Make no mistake about it, it is a blast of noise that rattles
the windows, that will make you jump up out of a sound sleep, that
will startle you off the couch when you are trying to watch a movie
or read a book. My dog howls in pain because of what it does to her
ears.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federal Railroad Administration:
http://www.fra.dot.gov/site/horns/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   For comments: http://dms.dot.gov and search for docket no. 6439
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-22-00 1749 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000622.0145 </DOCNO>
