<DOCNO> APW20000622.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Loophole in Russia Could Backfire  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW KRAMER
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- A legal loophole applying to holders of state or
military honors could open the prison gates for scores of convicted
and suspected murderers and other serious criminals, prosecutors
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   When parliament passed an amnesty law last month to commemorate
the 55th anniversary of Soviet Union over Germany, deputies said
they were acting to reduce overcrowding in the struggling,
disease-ridden prison system.
</P>
<P>
   The amnesty covered people who committed minor offenses, inmates
suffering from tuberculosis, pregnant women, invalids and those
holding state or military honors regardless of their crime.
</P>
<P>
   The lapse in Russia's usually draconian justice system rang
alarm bells at the prosecutor's office, which has persuaded
legislators to reconsider the law. The lower house of parliament,
the State Duma, may review it Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Those affected include war crimes suspects from Russia's
military campaign in Chechnya, such as a Russian army colonel
accused of raping and killing a Chechen teen-age girl this spring,
a spokesman for the military prosecutor's office said. The colonel
was earlier awarded two medals for his actions in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Also qualifying for amnesty are officers from an airborne unit
accused of planting a suitcase bomb that killed journalist Dmitry
Kholodov in 1994, prosecutor's office spokesman Sergei Ushakov
said.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Ministry spokesman said no one accused or convicted of
grave crimes has yet gone free under the amnesty, but some have
applied.
</P>
<P>
   Suspects in detention centers must admit guilt to take advantage
of the amnesty offer, which some have refused to do.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma, or lower house of parliament, agreed to review the law
after Prosecutor General Vladimir Ustinov sent a letter Wednesday
to the chamber saying 311 convicted and suspected murderers,
rapists and other serious criminals could be set free from jails in
and around Moscow alone.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Ministry, which controls prisons, reported a lower
figure of 40 to 60 in all of Russia, according to a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are socially dangerous people,'' said lawmaker Gennady
Raikov, and releasing the violent men ''is a rather unpleasant idea
for all of us,'' he said, speaking on NTV television news.
</P>
<P>
   The overstuffed and harsh conditions of the country's prisons
motivated the blanket amnesty, one of several passed in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has the largest per capita rate of incarceration in the
world and the second-largest prison population after the United
States, with about 1 million people behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Tuberculosis afflicts about 100,000 inmates, and about 10,000
inmates die from the illness each year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-22-00 1804 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000622.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Slip on High-Tech Retreat  </HEADLINE>
By SETH SUTEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq ran out of gas Thursday, cutting
short a five-day winning streak that had brought the average above
one important milestone -- 4,000 points -- and nearly above another,
where it began the year.
</P>
<P>
   A hearty selloff in technology stocks was to blame as investors
locked in profits following a weeks-long runup in major bellwethers
such as Oracle and Intel. The Nasdaq composite index fell 127.17,
or 3.1 percent, to 3,936.84.
</P>
<P>
   The damage was less severe in the Dow Jones industrial average,
which fell 121.62, or 1.2 percent, to close at 10,376.12.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq had breached the 4,000-point barrier on Tuesday for
the first time in more than two months. But selling in technology
shares Thursday spread to other sectors, bringing the overall
market lower.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're looking at some profit-taking in that sector, which has
been very strong,'' said Barry Hyman, senior equity analyst at
Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum. ''It looks like the big techs that ran
up are giving up some ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest losers included Micron Technology, which fell $5.75
to $85 as traders worried that the chip maker's earnings, due after
the close of trading, might fall short of expectations. The
earnings report actually beat analysts' estimates, however.
</P>
<P>
   Several tech bellwethers gave up some recently won ground,
including Intel, off $4.938 at $134.063; Oracle, down $4.688 at
$81.50; and Cisco Systems, off $2.875 at $64.563. Yahoo! fell
$11.125 to $131.688 after an analyst expressed concerns about the
outlook for online advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Mobile phone maker Nokia was also down on rumors that it was
buying telecom technology company Qualcomm. Nokia shares were off
$4.75 to $56.25, while Qualcomm's shares rose $3.758 to $68.25.
Neither company returned calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Thursday's trading, the Nasdaq index had climbed
for five straight sessions. The Nasdaq, which was close to breaking
even for the year on Wednesday, remained below its Dec. 31, 1999,
finish of 4,069.31. But it has come back from its low point on May
23, when the Nasdaq was down 28.6 percent from the end of last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Traders were also looking ahead to the Federal Reserve's regular
meeting Tuesday and Wednesday. There have been signals that the
economy has been slowing in response to the Fed's series of
interest rate increases, but investors are still bracing for the
possibility that the Fed may tighten credit further to keep
inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we're digesting the gains of the Nasdaq over the past
four weeks and looking ahead to the Fed meeting and the likelihood
of several earnings confessions next week,'' said Tom Galvin, chief
equity strategist at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said there was little effect from a rumor, quickly
denied by the Fed, that the central bank's chairman, Alan
Greenspan, was in an auto accident.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones by an 11-to-6 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where consolidated volume came to
$1.22 billion, down slightly from 1.21 billion shares Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was off 26.95 at 1,452.18, and
the Russell 2000 index was down 12.60 at 515.01.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.6 percent.
Germany's DAX index fell 0.7 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was down
1.0 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
