<HEADLINE> Pentagon Clears Korean War Medals  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon has cleared the way for U.S.
veterans of the Korean War to accept and wear a medal offered by
the South Korean government as a tribute to their service and
sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea originally offered the medal in 1951 to all who
fought under the United Nations banner, but the U.S. government
turned it down because American law at that time prohibited members
of the military from wearing medals issued by foreign governments.
Congress changed the law in 1954, but the South Korean government
didn't renew its offer of the ''Republic of Korea War Service
Medal'' until 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, South Korean Defense Minister Cho Seong-tae wrote to
Defense Secretary William Cohen to formally announce that his
government would provide the medal to all U.S. veterans of the war
or to their surviving next of kin. The U.S. Air Force will be in
charge of distributing the medals at no cost to veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Cho said the final decision to offer the medals was timed to
coincide with the 50th anniversary of the outbreak of the Korean
War on June 25.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon also announced Cohen will serve as host of the 50th
anniversary commemorative events Sunday at the Korean War Veterans
Memorial on the National Mall in Washington. President Clinton will
be the keynote speaker at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.8 million American military members served in Korea
during the war and nearly 37,000 were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The last foreign medal approved for U.S. military members to
wear was the Kuwait Liberation Medal for veterans of the 1991 war
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   To be eligible for the South Korean medal, U.S. veterans must
have served between the start of the war and the date of the
armistice that ended the fighting on July 27, 1953. They must have
served within the territorial limits of Korea, in the waters
immediately adjacent to Korea or while flying over Korea.
</P>
<P>
   To apply, veterans or the next-of-kin of deceased veterans must
provide a copy of their discharge paper, known as a DD-214. Details
on applying can be obtained by contacting the Air Force Personnel
Center at 1-800-558-1404 or by visiting the personnel center's Web
site at http://www.afpc.randolph.af.mil/awards.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Korean War 50th Anniversary site:
http://korea50.army.mil
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
