<HEADLINE> Korea, Japan, U.S. Talks Set  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Representatives from the United States, South
Korea and Japan will exchange views on the North Korean situation
next week in Honolulu, the U.S. State Department announced
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The three countries meet periodically to coordinate policy
toward North Korea. It will be the first such meeting since an
historic summit last week between North Korean leader Kim Jong Il
and his South Korean counterpart, President Kim Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Philip T. Reeker said the two-day
meeting will be used to discuss a ''range of issues in our ongoing
coordination of policy toward'' North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The trilateral consultations were formalized in Hawaii in April
1999 and are known as the Trilateral Coordination and Oversight
Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
