<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big-game losers avenge their defeats in 77th National Marbles Tournament </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILDWOOD, N.J. (AP) - What a difference a year made for two
young marbles aces.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Martinez, 14, of Grand Junction, Colo., and Larin Miller,
12, of Pittsburgh, captured top honors Thursday in the 77th annual
National Marbles Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez won in the boys' division, Miller in the girls'. Each
lost in the final game of competition in the 1999 tournament but
returned this year, along with 56 other boys and girls ages 8 to
14.
</P>
<P>
   ''This feels much better,'' said Martinez, a ninth-grader who
practices two hours a day and says the game of marbles is a
''blast.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many kinds of marbles games, but the one played at the
national tournament is called ''ringer.'' In it, two players line
up 13 marbles inside a circular 10-foot ring and take turns
shooting their object marbles into the target blue marbles,
knocking them out of the ring.
</P>
<P>
   The first person to knock out seven marbles wins the game.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez bested Ralph Dillon, 14, of New Milton, W.Va., in the
boys final; Miller defeated Stephanie Taylor, 13, of Cumberland,
Md., in the girls' division.
</P>
<P>
   She had been to the national tournament twice before, finishing
third in 1998 and second in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last year, she was in the championship and she choked,'' said
her mother, Barbara Miller, 44. ''I knew she wouldn't let that
happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   The winners get $2,000 college scholarships and a slew of small
gifts, including a trophy, a wristwatch, a T-shirt and a velvet
crown.
</P>
<P>
   The hard part is taking the throne. Each year, the winners are
seated in painted wooden thrones and showered with gifts. Then they
have to kiss each other.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have new royalty!'' said Beri Fox, the tournament's
secretary, as the two were seated. Then she ordered them to kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with about 200 people watching and dozens of cameras
trained on the winners, Martinez leaned over and kissed Miller on
the cheek, knocking the crown off her head and onto the ground. His
face was as red as a beet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 1828 </TRAILER>
