<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio misses vote, then news conference on fuel crunch  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - One week after missing a vote to create a
heating oil reserve for the Northeast, Rep. Rick Lazio was a
no-show Thursday at a news conference on soaring gas costs.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate race rival was to headline the
Capitol Hill event with other GOP lawmakers from the Northeast
blasting the Clinton administration for failing to combat rising
prices at the pump. But a half-hour into the news conference, Rep.
Sue Kelly, R-Westchester County, was passed a note saying Lazio
couldn't make it.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's campaign and the GOP conference had both issued releases
touting his appearance on the hot-button consumer issue.
</P>
<P>
   It was a scheduling conflict,'' a Lazio spokesman said
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Lazio was being interviewed by The New York Times for
a profile.
</P>
<P>
   The average price nationwide for a gallon of regular self-serve
gasoline has reached $1.68 - up nearly 44 percent from last
summer's average - and the high prices at the pump come after New
Yorkers spent a winter paying record prices for heating oil.
</P>
<P>
   After Lazio missed the news conference, reporters sought him out
at his office and were given a statement by aides that criticized
the Clinton administration and outlined three steps to address
rising gas costs.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman proposed exerting pressure on oil-producing
nations to increase production, opening up the U.S.'s strategic oil
reserve and reducing or repealing the federal gasoline tax.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio declined to speak to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   After the GOP news conference, a man who declined to identify
himself passed out news releases from the Democratic Message Group
attacking Lazio for missing last week's heating oil vote.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would have created a fuel reserve in the New York
Harbor, but was defeated by two votes.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day Clinton and Lazio's campaign traded
accusations over the congressman's support for a program to combat
domestic violence and rape.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has voted in support of the Violence Against Women Act and
has pledged to do so again, but Clinton criticized him for not
cosponsoring the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The act funds law enforcement, education and prevention programs
around the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 1829 </TRAILER>
