<HEADLINE> State Dept Offers Security Increase  </HEADLINE>
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Trying to assuage a senator who is holding up
seven ambassadorial nominees, State Department officials said
Thursday they will recommend increased security provisions for
foreign service employees.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rod Grams, R-Minn., blocked the nominations of the career
foreign service officers because they have compiled roughly 100
security violations, with one person responsible for more than 20.
He has not named the people or disclosed the violations.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Grossman, director general of the Foreign Service, told
Grams he will propose decreasing the number of infractions that
trigger disciplinary action and increasing penalties for security
incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before Grams' Senate Foreign Relations Committee's
international operations subcommittee, Grossman also said the State
Department would put a greater emphasis on ''security performance''
when considering nominations.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Grams indicated such moves could prompt him
to lift the holds.
</P>
<P>
   ''Like Ronald Reagan said -- trust but verify,'' he said. ''We
want to see some of these steps taken. Many could be taken within
weeks. (Secretary of State Madeleine Albright) will get this
information, and the quicker she responds, the quicker we can act
on the nominees.''
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, Grams criticized the State Department for
not placing more emphasis on security.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a result, State Department personnel are judged on the
basis of their cultural sensitivity but not on security,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman and David Carpenter, the assistant secretary of state
for diplomatic security, complimented Grams for raising the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your commitment has had an important impact on the
department,'' said Grossman, who took his job Monday. ''As I
promised in my confirmation hearing, you will find me ready to do
what we must to protect our secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department: http://www.state.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
