<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court rules trash fees are unconstitutional  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey counties cannot force trash
haulers and towns that no longer use their expensive trash burners
and landfills to help pay for them, the state Supreme Court ruled
Thursday in a split decision.
</P>
<P>
   So-called environmental investment charges are unconstitutional
because the Legislature never specifically authorized counties to
pass on such fees to former trash customers, the court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   But the justices postponed the effective date of their ruling
for three months, to give state lawmakers time to craft a solution
for counties left with huge trash facility debt.
</P>
<P>
   Absent legislative action in 90 days, Thursday's decision leaves
cash-strapped counties with few choices. They could raise trash
tipping fees for current customers, raise property taxes, or
default on their bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Some counties started imposing the special fees in the aftermath
of a 1997 federal court ruling that stripped counties of the power
to control the flow of trash within their borders. That ruling led
many haulers and municipalities to send their garbage to cheaper
facilities, depriving the counties of the revenue flow they were
counting on to make loan payments.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Passaic County planned to raise $80 million in
environmental investment charges to pay off debt it incurred
planning one landfill it later abandoned and reserving space in
another.
</P>
<P>
   But the city of Paterson, which no longer uses Passaic County's
trash services, fought the charge. On Thursday, the city celebrated
its victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''Paterson's future is brighter today than yesterday,'' said
Mayor Marty Burns in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Under the county's formula, the city was expected to pay more
than 30 percent of the trash fee for the entire county based on
past usage, far higher than its 11 percent portion of the county's
tax base, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Sandra Ayres, who represents Paterson, said it was
unfair for the county to unduly burden the city given that the
county used its overall property tax base to secure some of the
trash debt.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were considering an unlawful charge that requires us to
pay more? Of course we'd fight it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic, Cape May, Gloucester and Union counties are the others
that imposed environmental investment charges to recover their
share of the total $1.2 billion in trash debt statewide.
</P>
<P>
   These counties were relying on a 1977 statute that officials
said authorized them to charge both old and new customers a new fee
for old debt.
</P>
<P>
   But by a slim 4-3 margin, the justices disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the majority, Associate Justice Stein said that it
was too much of a stretch to use a ''mundane'' statute ''to address
an unanticipated statewide solid waste financial crisis that arose
20 years after the statute's adoption.
</P>
<P>
   ''No principle of statutory construction could condone so
extraordinary an interpretation,'' he wrote in the 57-page opinion.
</P>
<P>
   But in a dissent, Associate Justice Virginia Long said it was
not unreasonable to tap the 1977 law to allow the special charges
to stand - especially given the consequences if the counties were
left with no other recourse to pay their debt.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no reason why we should adopt an equal (not better)
interpretation that would have the effect of creating a fiscal
emergency and compelling legislative intervention,'' she said of
the majority.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Benjamin Clarke, who represented Passaic County, said he
hopes state lawmakers finally take notice of the problem, which has
been brewing since the 1997 federal court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has clearly been a difficult political issue and
continues to be one. But this decision obviously creates
substantial additional pressure to implement remedial
legislation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Celeste Carpiano, executive director of the New Jersey
Association of Counties, agreed that the new deadline and the risk
of widespread bond defaults will force action.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman promised cooperation to meet the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will work with the Legislature to develop a long-term
solution to the stranded debt problem,'' she said in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
