<HEADLINE> U.S. Questions Chinese News Bureau  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Chinese news agency Xinhua has created a
flurry of news itself with the revelation it is buying a building
near the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   After the planned purchase became known, the State Department
said Thursday it has reminded the Chinese Embassy that a
15-year-old law requires it to apply for permission whenever the
government-affiliated news agency wants to buy or sell real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have informed them that they must make such a request, and
the State Department will have 60 days in which to authorize or
deny such a request when it's made,'' State Department spokesman
Philip T. Reeker said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Xinhua has said it plans to use the seven-story building in
Arlington, Va., -- less than a mile from the Pentagon -- for a new
news room and for housing. The building provides a distant view of
some of the Pentagon outer wall.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said it would evaluate whether the purchase would
pose a security problem.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Defense Department was concerned, spokesman Kenneth
Bacon said: ''It's not new to us, the idea that people might want
to watch or listen to what goes on in the building, and We've been
living in that environment ... for over 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We obviously have a number of countermeasures that we've
installed over time to defeat or foil surveillance,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon and State Department learned of the Chinese plans
Wednesday when the Washington Times reported it and quoted analysts
who feared it could be used for spying.
</P>
<P>
   Xinhua's bureau chief, Jiang Liu, denied the agency is engaged
in spying, and Chinese Embassy spokesman Zhang Yuanyuan said Xinhua
was advised by its American lawyers that it had followed U.S. laws.
</P>
<P>
   Reeker said the Chinese were notified in 1985 that they would
have to obtain prior authorization for any purchase or sale of real
property by Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
   ''The restriction remains in place today, and Xinhua is aware of
it,'' he said. He said there is no record that Xinhua notified the
department of plans to purchase the Arlington property.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang, speaking for the embassy, said Chinese officials
understood that diplomats but not news organizations were required
to get permission for property purchases. He said Xinhua's
personnel do not carry diplomatic visas, and the agency is
registered in Virginia as a private, profit-making company.
</P>
<P>
   ''The news agency wants to do everything correctly,'' he said
and officials plan to discuss the issue with the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang Liu, the Xinhua bureau chief, called suggestions that the
news agency was involved in spying ''a tale from 'The Arabian
Nights.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
