<HEADLINE> State approves millions for vocational technical schools  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The state Board of Education has approved
plans for millions of dollars in renovations to vocational
technical schools in Manchester, Hartford and Danbury.
</P>
<P>
   Howell Cheney Regional Vocational-Technical School in Manchester
would get a $45 million face lift and expansion. In a meeting
Wednesday, the board also approved plans for renovations and
expansions at A.I. Prince Vocational-Technical School in Hartford,
estimated to cost $67.9 million, and at Henry Abbott Regional
Vocational-Technical School in Danbury, at a price of $50.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   Those schools - which Education Commissioner Theodore S. Sergi
called the ''neediest'' in the 17-school vo-tech system - would be
the first to undergo major renovations since 1999, when the
legislature agreed to allow the State Board of Education to seek
state bonding funds for renovations through the same process as
other school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is historic for our school system,'' Cheney Tech Director
Bruce Sievers said. ''This will begin the biggest phase of
construction since the 1950s, when many of our schools were
built.''
</P>
<P>
   The board's action meets a June 30 deadline for districts to
submit proposed school projects to the Education Department, if
they want them included in the list of construction projects that
will go before the 2001 legislature.
</P>
<P>
   But the board directed the staff to fine-tune and prioritize the
proposals. Board members said they were concerned about the large
amount of money involved, and Sergi said the board will have to be
able to justify all the work to Gov. John G. Rowland's office.
</P>
<P>
   The projects would create more space for trade areas and
classrooms and renovate other sections of the colleges.
</P>
</TEXT>
