<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian land claim headed to court  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - Saying neither side was genuinely
committed to negotiations, a discouraged federal judge ruled
Thursday the Oneida Indian land claim dispute will be settled in
court.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Neal P. McCurn said failure to agree
on a sales tax formula was the deal breaker, pushing the protracted
fight from the negotiating table to the court room. He will set a
court date in the near future for litigation he said ''undoubtedly
will take years to run its course.''
</P>
<P>
   In his four-page decision, McCurn said ''there is no point in
proceeding any further.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent round of negotiations just two weeks ago, all sides
went home without making progress toward a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   McCurn had ordered the Oneida Indian nations of New York,
Wisconsin and Canada, the U.S. Department of Justice, Madison and
Oneida counties, and the state of New York to explain their
positions on the ''gut'' issues that have been holding up a
settlement on the largest and oldest Indian land dispute in the
eastern United States.
</P>
<P>
   The parties have been trying since February 1999 to sort out how
much land the Oneidas can have for their reservation in the two
central New York counties and how much authority their sovereign
government can assert on that land. There also are legal questions
about a sales tax formula and gaming rights on the land.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is certainly enough blame to go around for the fact that
following a full day of intense mediation efforts ... settlement
efforts were halted,'' McCurn wrote. ''The court cannot help but
observe, however, that on that day, as throughout much of the
mediation process, not all of the parties were genuinely committed
to settling this lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Oneida Nation spokesman Mark Emery said he is confident a trial
will uphold the Indian nation's position.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody would have been happier with a resolution
obviously,'' Emery said. ''Certainly the judge put blame on
everybody and certainly everybody had some share of that blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Oneida County Executive Ralph Eannace could immediately be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   McCurn chided the New York Oneidas, the counties and the state
government for their stubbornness, saying not one was willing to
''subordinate their own self-interests in an attempt to arrive at a
fair settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oneidas are seeking compensation for 250,000 acres of land
they claim the state purchased illegally in the late 18th and early
19th centuries. Yearlong negotiations broke off April 4.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a settlement, the counties have insisted the
1,100-member Oneida Indian Nation of New York pay property taxes
and collect sales taxes from non-Indians who purchase goods on
reservation land.
</P>
<P>
   The Oneidas have offered to pay the counties $20 million, in the
form of $1 million each year for 20 years, to offset sales taxes
they say sovereign Indian nations do not have to collect. They also
have offered to set aside $25 million of the settlement money for
the counties to offset unpaid property taxes and limit their
reservation to 40,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   The state, meanwhile, has asked for 25 percent of the Oneidas'
Turning Stone casino earnings, and negotiators for the state and
federal governments have offered to contribute equally to a $500
million pot of settlement money. That plan, however, would have to
be approved by both the state Legislature and Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 1901 </TRAILER>
