<HEADLINE> Fire in Australian Hostel Kills 8  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) -- A pre-dawn fire tore through a hostel
filled with international backpackers in eastern Australia Friday,
killing at least eight people, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters used hydraulic platforms to pull 70 people to
safety from the blazing, wooden building in Childers, 130 miles
north of Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
   Nine people were treated at a hospital for smoke inhalation.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-six people were believed inside the two-story structure
when the blaze broke out around 12:30 a.m., said local fire
commissioner Jeff Wright. Eight bodies were recovered and eight
people were unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   firefighters put out the blaze after about four hours.
Authorities were searching through the ruins and trying to
determine the cause of the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   The identities of the victims weren't immediately known.
Officials said many of the hostel residents were British working as
seasonal workers picking fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Heidrich, the editor of the town's newspaper, was one of
the first on the scene, and said terrified survivors were in shock
when he got there.
</P>
<P>
   ''The residents of the hostel who had been evacuated were
sitting across the road watching the hostel burn,'' Heidrich told
Australian Broadcasting Corp. radio.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said that at the height of the fire, residents fled
across adjoining rooftops to escape the flames.
</P>
</TEXT>
