<HEADLINE> GOP Pushes Forward Disclosure Bill  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans pushed forward legislation that
would require well-established nonprofit organizations to disclose
the names of people who pay for any political activity.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats complained the bill was too broad, probably
unconstitutional and intended to destroy a legitimate effort to
force newly popular, often secretive political groups to disclose
their donors. Democrats and their GOP ally, Sen. John McCain, also
complained the bill included labor unions but not corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was hoping the Republicans really wanted to pass something
but there doesn't appear to be a good-faith interest in that. They
quite clearly don't want a bill,'' said Rep. Lloyd Doggett,
D-Texas, who has led the Democratic effort in the House. ''I think
the idea is to just run the clock out.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill was approved by the House Ways and Means Committee
Thursday on a party line vote, 23-14, and moves to the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   It's the GOP answer to a Democratic bill that aims to give the
public more information about groups that organize under section
527 of the tax code, which is set aside for political
organizations. Under current law, these groups can appear from
nowhere and do not have to tell the public anything about
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans complained that it was unfair to require
disclosure by these groups when other nonprofits across the
political spectrum also engage in similar attempts to influence
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''It shouldn't be disclosure for some and secrecy for others,''
said Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas. ''It should be
disclosure for all and sunshine on the entire political process.''
</P>
<P>
   One of these groups that organize under that portion of the tax
code is tied to House GOP Whip Tom Delay, R-Texas, who on Thursday
fired off a letter to McCain, complaining about McCain's
castigation of the groups using the 527 section.
</P>
<P>
   ''By employing emotionally overwrought rhetoric that places
Americans contributing to these groups on the same level as evil
criminals, you rashly condemn many citizens who are simply pursuing
their First Amendment right to join the debate,'' Delay wrote to
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, R-Ariz., brushed him off with a reference to a World War
II battle: ''In the words of General McAuliffe, when asked by the
Germans to surrender at Bastogne: 'Nuts.'''
</P>
<P>
   All of these groups -- no matter where they fall in the tax code
-- manage to avoid reporting their contributors and spending to the
Federal Election Commission by avoiding use of words such as ''vote
for'' and ''vote against'' in their ads and materials. As far as
the FEC is concerned, these groups say, they are simply discussing
issues.
</P>
<P>
   But section 527 groups, by registering in this section of the
tax code, are declaring themselves to be engaged in politics, not
issues. Early this month, McCain and others persuaded the Senate to
require them to disclose donors and spending.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats pushed similar legislation, but GOP leaders
argued that the law should also include other non-profit groups.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP bill crafted by Rep. Amo Houghton, R-N.Y., goes too
far, said Doggett and his Democratic colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   They complained the bill was probably unconstitutional. The
courts have said that people have a right to privately join
together in associations. Democrats suggested getting around this
by requiring all groups to disclose contributors, but only for
spending in the months preceding an election. Republicans insisted
on disclosure year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also complained that the bill excluded for-profit
corporations and could be interpreted to include voter registration
drives, lobbying on legislation and other activity not directly
tied to an election.
</P>
<P>
   Doggett said that he believed Houghton was sincere in his effort
but was forced by GOP leaders -- namely Delay -- to write a bill that
could not pass.
</P>
<P>
   But Trent Duffy, a spokesman for Republicans on Ways and Means,
said the Democrats' really objection was that the legislation
required unions to say who is paying for their communications with
members when they work to get out the vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
