<HEADLINE> Possible Flu Vaccine Shortage Seen  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Influenza vaccines could arrive a month later
than usual this fall and shortages are possible, the government
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A notice was sent to health care agencies asking them to plan
their mass flu vaccinations for November rather than the usual
mid-October start.
</P>
<P>
   ''Several vaccine manufacturers are having difficulty getting
one of the vaccine components to grow as well as they expected,''
said Nancy Cox, chief of the influenza branch of the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said that and other production problems could also cause a
shortage of vaccine but the CDC won't know that until later on in
the summer. ''At the current time we expect there will be
sufficient vaccine available to immunize those at high risk,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals, nursing homes and health care organizations are
beginning to plan campaigns to immunize large numbers of people and
need to know now that they might not get the vaccine at the usual
time, Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   If a substantial shortfall occurs, the CDC will recommend making
it a priority to vaccinate those most at risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
