<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Frequent 'atrocious' discriminatory conduct alleged in $1 billion lawsuit </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A group of 50 current and former minority
employees of the Jacob K. Javits Convention Center of New York
alleged in a $1 billion lawsuit Thursday that they were subject to
''atrocious discriminatory conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan portrayed
the convention center as a cesspool of graphic racial, religious
and sexual slurs ''designed to deprive plaintiffs of their dignity
and their humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   It said the center ''subjects its minority employees to a
deplorable work environment rife with discrimination and
hostility.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Eisgrau, a Javits spokesman, declined to comment ''since
it's in litigation now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Javits Center has tax-exempt status and its board is
appointed by Gov. George Pataki and top state officials.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit asserted violations of the U.S. Constitution as well
as state and local laws. It sought $500 million in compensatory
damages and $500 million in punitive damages, along with a court
order preventing discriminatory conduct in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs included 11 carpenters and 31 freight handlers,
both job classifications that limit the hours an employee works
according to whether there are events at the convention center
requiring their expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an employee pool that is evenly divided between whites
and minorities, a high percentage of those chosen for a seniority
list of people actually called to work are white, according to the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   It alleged that a seniority list of 60 names included 50 whites,
seven black men and three Hispanic men.
</P>
<P>
   The workers allege that other violations and insults were
repeatedly committed by a group of managers and foremen, all white
men of Irish decent except for one Irish woman and one black man.
</P>
<P>
   The lone black foreman was promoted to the position only after
convention center managers became aware that a federal
discrimination lawsuit was in the works, the lawsuit alleged.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs said they were routinely subjected to derogatory
racial slurs and sexually offensive innuendo.
</P>
<P>
   ''The vicious slurs were shamelessly condoned by top level
management. Even worse, some top level managers participated in
this horrendous conduct,'' the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   It singled out Richard Powers, a member of the management staff
responsible for maintenance and operation of the Javits Center,
including hiring, firing, promotion and discipline of employees.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleged that every plaintiff had heard Powers
repeatedly use ethnic slurs and make derogatory comments about
women such as: ''I don't want women in the building, especially not
black women, unless they work for housekeeping.''
</P>
<P>
   Powers, reached at the convention center Thursday, listened to
the allegations against him and then declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs also allege that racially oppressive and
threatening depictions remain on bathroom walls at Javits for
months or years, including drawings of a black man being lynched
and Nazi swastikas.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit said one of the plaintiffs, David Cokely, had
complained about being called a series of racial slurs and later
found the phrase ''David Cokely is a black bastard who will die''
written on a bathroom wall.
</P>
<P>
   His car tires were slashed, his windows broken, another employee
urinated in his Gatorade bottle and others repeatedly made death
threats against him, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit also said that a foreman was seen on the docks one
day searching for a black employee while holding a bunch of bananas
and yelling, ''Where's my monkeys?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 1933 </TRAILER>
