<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Riding No. 7 Into the Lion's Den  </HEADLINE>
By JIM LITKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bible doesn't go into much detail about how Daniel arrived
in the lion's den, but you can be sure it wasn't on the No. 7
train.
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker's desire to come to New York next week and face his
demons is understandable. Almost admirable, in fact. But it's also
shortsighted, ill-timed, unnecessarily expensive and unlikely to do
anyone any good -- least of all Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a tourist arrived in Gotham this unprepared, it
was Jack Lemmon in the 1970 comedy called ''The Out-of-Towners.''
He played a guy who goes to New York for a job interview and ends
up on a hellish train ride, gets fleeced by hustlers and chased by
cops. The difference in real life is that all this could happen to
Rocker, too, and he might still have to pitch his way out of a
bases-loaded jam in snarling, seething Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Those who insist Rocker will have to get this over with sooner
or later are right. And not just for the macho value of being able
to say he wasn't run out of town. He has to know that no
organization will waste a roster spot on a player who can't
accompany the team to New York. But if I'm Rocker's travel agent,
the recommendation is a nice three-night package in late September
instead. Maybe the last week of the season, when the Atlanta Braves
make their only other appearance at Shea. The timing has to be
better.
</P>
<P>
   Relief pitching is a high-wire act. It requires not just a lot
of sound body parts working in unison, but nerves of steel and more
than a fair share of good luck. Rocker is having trouble with all
three right now. Struggling is something he did very little of in
his almost-unbroken run from preps to pros, but Rocker is making up
for lost time.
</P>
<P>
   At home against the Cubs on Wednesday, he gave up five earned
runs in only one-third of an inning. He only yielded one hit, but
walked four batters and hit another. His wildness reminded
Chicago's Mark Grace of another reliever whose wackiness cost him a
job before his time.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's Mitch Williams -- with 10 mph more,'' Grace said, shaking
his head. ''I don't know what they're going to do, but they have to
do something.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves don't have a plan, either. They can't give him
away and, right now, they can't get much for him. After his
disastrous stint the other night, Rocker sat in the dugout next to
pitching coach Leo Mazzone. That would be the same guy who said
this when the famous Sports Illustrated story came out last
December:
</P>
<P>
   ''Baseball's a very humbling game. The first thing I think about
after I hear about this, he's going to go out and blow himself out.
One of his teammates might punch him out. Something's going to go
wrong now with his career. And you watch, it'll end up going
straight down the tubes.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker's grip is tenuous enough and a trip to New York could
push him over the edge. When he was sent down to the minors
recently, the Braves said he had to work on his control. He threw
30 pitches against the Cubs and only nine for strikes. He is
averaging a hit per inning worked. His earned-run average is 5.85,
and his walk-to-strikeout ratio is 1-to-1. It's clear he has no
control.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Rocker could take comfort in not being the only member
of his fraternity who is struggling. Billy Wagner of the Astros was
one of the game's best closers last season, converting 39 saves in
42 opportunities with a 1.49 ERA. This season, he's blown nine of
15 saves and perhaps the tendon in his throwing arm as well. One
difference between him and Rocker is that Wagner has plenty of
friends in the clubhouse and more than a few supporters in the
Houston front office.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason Rocker's even on a big-league roster is because
of yet another problem with oft-injured Rudy Seanez. Like everybody
else in baseball, even the Braves are desperate for pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Rocker home would seem to benefit almost everyone, but
general manager John Schuerholz sounded indifferent when asked
about Rocker's plan to ride the No. 7 train to next week's series.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a nonissue for me,'' he said. ''Guys travel to the
ballpark however they like.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be an issue, though, for New York, which will have to
pay for hundreds of extra cops to be on hand to ensure Rocker is
safe riding past Woody Allen's film studio and through
neighborhoods packed with Asians and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   It's small comfort, but Rocker can count on one thing. If he
makes it to the end of the line, the No. 7 will drop him off closer
to Shea than his pitches have been around the plate lately.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated
Press. Write to him at jlitke@ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-22-00 1936 </TRAILER>
