<HEADLINE> Officers shoot man with machete in White Plains  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - A 21-year-old man who was brandishing
a machete in downtown White Plains on Thursday was shot when he
lunged, screaming, at two police officers, a police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Guy, whose address was not made public, survived the
shooting and was recovering from surgery at White Plains Hospital,
said city police Capt. Peter Viviano.
</P>
<P>
   The officers, whose names were not released, were taken to
hospitals for treatment of emotional trauma; one was admitted at
the Westchester Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Viviano said Guy was spotted on the corner of Chester Avenue and
East Post Road with his 2-foot-long machete. A passer-by went into
the nearby Westchester County probation offices and notified a
county policeman.
</P>
<P>
   That policeman, joined by a probation officer, ordered Guy to
drop the machete. He refused twice, then screamed and charged at
the officers, Viviano said. They fired their service weapons and
Guy was hit in the abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   The county police and probation departments were investigating
the shootings, Viviano said. Guy was charged with first-degree
attempted murder.
</P>
</TEXT>
