<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ivana Trump sues Italian television show for $3 million  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Ivana Trump has filed a $3 million lawsuit
against a television station in Italy, alleging that employees of a
show on which she appeared dropped a large quantity of water on
her.
</P>
<P>
   Trump says in court papers that the dousing made her sick,
ruined her $3,000 dress and made her lose a pair of $25,000
earrings made by jeweler Harry Winston. She said she spent $400 on
emergency medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was not treated with respect on that show,'' said Trump's
lawyer, Dan Harrington. ''She's a nice lady. We're not going to let
them get away with that.'' He would not elaborate on the incident
or the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed Wednesday in Manhattan's State Supreme Court,
Trump said she was asked in June 1999 to appear in Italy on a
television program called ''Scherzi A Parte,'' a show similar to
''Candid Camera.''
</P>
<P>
   The show contacted Trump's agent, the William Morris Agency, and
sent the request along with the note from the show's producer,
Alessandra Cartanese, saying, ''I will be sending the story board
of the prank (joke) that could be done on her. Obviously she would
have to agree to it.''
</P>
<P>
   In July, Trump was told that the program's first story board, in
which a woman and a dog relieve themselves and a woman changes a
baby's diaper, was ''a little vulgar,'' so the producers had come
up with something else.
</P>
<P>
   After Trump approved a new sketch, the producers agreed to pay
her $18,000 for her TV appearance on July 8, 1999, to be aired
later. On July 6, Trump left New York for Italy on a flight paid
for by the television show.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the show, court papers say, while other guests
talked, ''loud sounds of thunder were heard'' and defendants
''caused water to be dropped from a high elevation onto plaintiff's
head and body.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump suffered ''bodily harm, shock, chills, nervousness, high
fever, nausea, embarrassment and severe emotional distress,'' court
papers say.
</P>
<P>
   Court papers say the show's producers deliberately lied to Trump
about what was supposed to happen on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ''Defendants intended to deceive and trick (Trump) into
appearing on their television show by giving (her) the appearance
that the show was to be professional and conducted in a manner
suited to the caliber and international status of Ivana Trump,''
the papers say.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, court papers say, the show's employees ''planned to
intentionally drop water onto (Trump) from a high elevation with
the purpose to shock and embarrass'' her so her reaction could be
captured on tape.
</P>
<P>
   Trump's lawsuit names the television company that produces the
show, RETI Televisive Italiane (RTI); Cartanese and another
individual associated with the show; and A.C. Promotions, a
productions and casting agency in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   A person at RTI's New York office said no one there could
comment on Trump's lawsuit. There was no answer at a phone at RTI's
offices in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit asks $1 million in general damages and $2 million in
punitive damages, as well as payment for Trump's ruined or lost
personal property.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 1942 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000622.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Pilot in fatal crash took medication for chronic migraines  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - The pilot of a small plane that crashed into
a Newark street last year was taking pain medication for migraines
that should have kept him from flying, a federal report said
Thursday. The pilot and three others were killed in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board investigators also
concluded that two of the plane's three gyroscopes weren't turning
at the time of the crash. Pilot Itzhak Jacoby, 56, of Bethesda,
Md., had reported gyroscope problems on the Beechcraft Bonanza S35
before crashing on Nov. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said that failed gyroscopes could have doomed the flight
that crashed into a factory and barreled down a street, shedding
its wings and tail before hitting a Kentucky Fried Chicken
restaurant. Twenty-five people were injured on the ground and the
plane caused more than $1 million in property damage.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB said Jacoby should not have been flying while taking
Fiorinal, a medication for migraines that contains the sedative
butalbital.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB report did not offer conclusions on whether the
gyroscope problem or Jacoby's use of Fiorinal caused the crash. A
final report listing a probable cause is expected within a month,
NTSB investigator David Muzio said.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that Jacoby had been taking Fiorinal since 1976
and had a history of severe migraines, but never mentioned headache
problems or taking prescription medication on applications for FAA
medical certification.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pilots cannot fly with anything that causes sedation,'' said
Neil Nadler, a senior aviation medical examiner from Parsippany who
awards medical certificates to Continental Airlines and private
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   If a pilot who took Fiorinal and had severe migraine headaches
applied for certification, ''I would not clear him,'' Nadler said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby, a retired National Institutes of Health scientist; his
wife, Gail, 50; and their 13-year-old daughter, Atira, were killed
when the plane crashed a few minutes after takeoff from Linden
Municipal Airport. The Jacobys were headed to Dulles International
Airport in Washington, D.C., after visiting family. Alfred Walker,
59, of Newark, died on Jan. 21 of injuries he sustained on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy found 2.84 milligrams per liter of butalbital in
Jacoby's urine. The sedative is found in Fiorinal. Butalbital is
''habit-forming and potentially abusable'' with side effects of
drowsiness and dizziness, according to the 1999 edition of the
Physician's Desk Reference.
</P>
<P>
   On July 16, 1989, the report said, Jacoby called a nurse on the
phone, told her he was suffering from severe migraines and asked
for a prescription refill that would last him until the next
morning. At that time, Jacoby was taking one Fiorinal every four to
six hours, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby was prescribed over 6,000 Fiorinal tablets between 1992
and October 1999, the NTSB said. A history of chronic migraine or
tension headaches would keep pilots from flying, according to the
FAA's 1999 guide for aviation medical examiners.
</P>
<P>
   The headaches often need medication to cure, ''and in most
instances, the use of such medications is disqualifying because
they may interfere with a pilot's alertness and functioning,'' the
guidelines state.
</P>
<P>
   Nadler said that lying on FAA medical application forms is
punishable by up to five years in federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby held a commercial pilot certificate and had logged 5,800
hours of flight time, 120 hours in the last six months, the NTSB
said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators examined three gyroscopes, which help to balance
the plane and tell the pilot which direction it is heading and
whether it is pointing up or down. The gyroscope from the attitude
indicator was operating at the time of the crash, while the
horizontal-situation indicator's gyroscope was not, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   The turn coordinator's gyroscope, considered a backup, was not
working, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Gyroscope failure can render key cockpit indicators failure and
cause a plane to crash, said Drew Steketee, a spokesman for the
Aircraft Owners and Pilots Association in Frederick, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is a very, very tough place to be,'' Steketee said.
''We've lost 747s due to instrument failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Steketee, who said he knew Jacoby for 10 years, said that Jacoby
had mentioned ''a slight problem'' with headaches in the past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
