<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hartford sergeant defends himself against sex-related charges  </HEADLINE>
jchfc
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A Hartford police sergeant took the stand
in his federal corruption trial Thursday, telling a jury he did not
abuse two prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have the wrong man, and before the living God Jehovah I
did not do any of the crimes I'm charged with,'' Albert Beauchamp
testified.
</P>
<P>
   The government accuses Beauchamp of violating the civil rights
of the two women. Prosecutors claim that at various times,
Beauchamp took the prostitutes in his cruiser to secluded spots in
Hartford's South End, urinated in front of each of them, fondled
one of them, and during one incident, directing one of the women to
perform an erotic dance for a retiring captain.
</P>
<P>
   Beauchamp is one of six Hartford police officers indicted last
year on federal corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   He is the first to go to trial. Four others have pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Beauchamp, 35, faces a maximum sentence of three years in prison
if convicted. He has been suspended from the force pending the
outcome of the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
