<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers, Whitman staff cobble $21.5B budget, up $270M since January </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Lawmakers and the Whitman administration
reached agreement Thursday on a $21.5 billion spending plan for the
new fiscal year beginning July 1.
</P>
<P>
   If approved intact as expected, the new budget when signed by
Gov. Christie Whitman will represent a 10-percent increase in
spending from the budget signed into law one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed budget is up about $270 million from the $21.3
billion spending plan Whitman unveiled in January and gave to the
Legislature for consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the administration has sought about $154 million in
additional spending, according to spokesman Peter McDonough, most
of it to provide increased funds for poor and urban schools to
remain in compliance with a Supreme Court mandate.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Legislature has inserted $123 million in
increases in state programs or for special projects, according to
Sen. Robert Littell, R-Sussex, the Senate budget committee
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Leonard Lance, R-Hunterdon, the chairman of the
Assembly budget committee, verified the numbers. He said his chief
priority for the fiscal 2000-2001 year had been to maintain an $850
million reserve, or ''surplus,'' which had been accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   In full numbers, the budget will be about $21.53 billion, up 1.3
percent from the $21.253 billion budget proposed in January and
10.3 percent from the $19.514 billion budget signed last June.
Earlier reports Thursday pegged the budget at closer to $21.6
billion but both McDonough and Littell said small parts had been
sliced out.
</P>
<P>
   The major components of the budget, such as more than $600
million for transportation projects, were not in dispute. Rather,
Senate and Assembly members were at odds with Treasury department
staff or each other over relatively small-ticket items being
changed or inserted into the spending plan.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the Senate budget committee, Joseph Kyrillos,
R-Monmouth, said, ''There are no big disputes over big things.
There are big disputes over little things.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonough said, ''I think they were within $50 million of each
other for the last 48 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislative staff continued working on the final budget
legislation into the night Thursday, since many last-minute changes
require myriad adjustments in mathematics and legal language. They
were not expected to have it finished and filed until after 3 a.m.
Friday, according to Rosemary Pramuk, chief budget analyst for the
Senate Republican staff.
</P>
<P>
   In what has become a bizarre annual ritual, the Legislature
actually remained in official session late into the night Thursday
even though all of the lawmakers had gone home by early evening.
</P>
<P>
   The empty Assembly and Senate were scheduled to remain in
session, technically speaking, until the dawn hours Friday to allow
introduction of a final budget bill with all of the numbers. This
odd step is necessary so that the budget can be put to a vote by
both houses next week and signed by the governor in time for the
June 30 deadline set in the state's constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Full text of the budget bill, including special add-on programs
for specific legislative districts or projects, will not be made
public until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   McDonough would not comment on which of these added programs
Whitman might delete with her unique line-item veto power. ''One
person's program is another person's pork,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   --:
</P>
<P>
   Full text of bills available at the Office of Legislative
Services Web site located at http://www.njleg.state.nj.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
