<HEADLINE> More Testimony in Umpires Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Sandy Alderson, the new boss of baseball's
umpires, completed his testimony Thursday in the grievance
attempting to regain the jobs of 22 umps released last September.
</P>
<P>
   Alderson began his testimony during the first week of May and
was cross-examined Thursday by the Major League Umpires
Association, the union that represented umps before this season.
</P>
<P>
   He was followed to the stand by Robert Kheel, a longtime lawyer
for the National League who headed negotiations for the umpires'
old labor contract, which expired Dec. 31. Kheel was scheduled to
resume testifying Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The sides hope to complete testimony in the case by the end of
next week. There is no indication when arbitrator Alan Symonette
will make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   The 22, a group that includes Richie Garcia, Frank Pulli, Terry
Tata, Eric Gregg and Joe West, lost their jobs after a mass
resignation plan failed. The MLUA then filed a grievance, arguing
owners shouldn't have released the 22.
</P>
<P>
   During the offseason, umpires voted out the MLUA, which was
heavily supported by NL umps, and replaced it with the World
Umpires Association, which has the support of most AL umps.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, talks between the new union and owners appear to be
at a standstill. The terms of the expired contract have been
extended through June 30. After that, either side can give 14 days'
notice it intends a work stoppage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
