<HEADLINE> Cards' Orosco Encouraged  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Jesse Orosco might not have to go on the
disabled list, after all.
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old St. Louis Cardinals reliever had swelling in his
elbow after his outing Wednesday night. But on Thursday, he said it
felt much better.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll treat it, get some ice, and see how it goes,'' Orosco
said. ''I've just got a little swelling in there, and we'll see if
it goes down.''
</P>
<P>
   Orosco has made two appearances since he was activated June 9.
He's first on the career list with 1,096 games.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Walt Jocketty said trainers didn't think the
injury was serious. Orosco said the elbow didn't hurt until after
he finished pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's never been hurt before, so he doesn't know how to act,''
Jocketty said. ''He'll take a few days off and we'll see how it
goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Orosco said it was strange to be having problems after a long,
mostly injury-free career.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're talking 22 years of pitching and nothing's ever
happened,'' Orosco said. ''This all of a sudden bit me. Hopefully,
as the season goes on that will improve and maybe I can come back
to throwing back-to-back days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
