<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Caddie back at Cadillac NFL Classic despite cancer  </HEADLINE>
By TOM CANAVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFTON, N.J. (AP) - As long as Brian Deasy caddies on the PGA
Senior Tour, the pin incident on the next-to-last hole of the 1998
Cadillac NFL Classic is going to follow him.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow caddies and pros still tease the 39-year-old about the
mistake which almost cost Bob Dickson the championship.
</P>
<P>
   It's good-natured, and Deasy smiles a lot telling the story
about how he left the pin in on the par-3, 17th hole as Dickson was
attempting a 60-foot birdie putt while battling Jim Colbert and
Larry Nelson for the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Had the putt hit the pin, it would have been a disastrous
two-stroke penalty and Dickson's 25-year victory drought never
would have ended two holes later in a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to make any excuses,'' said Deasy, who was
working that week because Dickson's regular caddie, Mark Bolick,
needed the week off and Deasy's regular boss, Vincente Fernandez,
was skipping the tournament. ''I choked.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Deasy sees it, the incident happened for a reason. He
doesn't know why. He just accepts it.
</P>
<P>
   It the same approach he's taken since three months later in 1998
when he felt a lump on the side of his neck while watching
television in a hotel in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month later, doctors gave him the diagnosis. He had
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, a slow-spreading cancer, and it had been
found in his lymph system and bone marrow.
</P>
<P>
   After being examined at home in Clifton Park, N.Y., Deasy went
to two of the nation's top facilities that treat cancer. Doctors at
Dana Farber in Boston have given him 12 years to live. The experts
at Sloan Kettering in New York City give him eight.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe with technology, with the hopes of maybe finding
ways to treat what I have, that there is a good chance I can live a
lot longer,'' Deasy said Thursday on the eve of this year's
Cadillac NFL Golf Classic, his first return to the course since
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''I also have a tremendous attitude in the fact that I am not
going to give in to this thing,'' Deasy said. ''I'm not just going
to feel sorry for myself and dwell on the negatives. I stay real
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Deasy, who grew up in Glen Cove on Long Island and started
caddying at Piping Rock at the age of 12, undergoes blood work
every 12 weeks and CAT scans every six months. His cancer is not in
remission and the last CAT scan he took showed that a couple of
lymph nodes had gotten a little bigger.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Deasy has not taken either chemotherapy or radiation,
but knows he might need it soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''It could be a year from now, it could be five years or 10
years, you never know,'' said Deasy, who went to Sloan-Kettering on
Wednesday for more tests. ''It all depends on how my illness
progresses.''
</P>
<P>
   While admitting to some fear and nervousness, Deasy said the
cancer is not dominating his life.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he took Fernandez out to the 17th hole and the two
recreated the scene from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Deasy showed Fernandez where the pin placement was and where
Dickson's ball was and they talked about how the shadows made it
hard to see the pin.
</P>
<P>
   ''I even said to Vincente as a goof the first time we play the
hole this year I'll just leave the pin and say, 'Have someone tend
it' as a goof,'' Deasy said.
</P>
<P>
   Deasy said the problem in 1998 was that when he normally reads a
putt, he takes the pin out and carries it back to where his pro is
lining up the putt. Because of the shadows, Dickson told him to put
the pin back in as they were making the read.
</P>
<P>
   ''I stepped to the right and Dickson got up and hit the putt
almost immediately,'' Deasy said. ''If Jim Colbert didn't say
something after the putt, neither one of us would have known the
pin was still in.''
</P>
<P>
   It's made for a great story for the last two years wherever
Deasy has gone on the senior tour. It's a story he would like to
tell for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will not give into this thing,'' Deasy said. ''I just won't.
Another thing that has changed in my life is when I hear about
cancer it has so much more meaning because I have it. I can
understand what people are going through.
</P>
<P>
   ''It might sound crazy, but getting the cancer, a lot of
positive things have come out of this. I'm very grateful for a lot
of things, my wife, my friends. I'm a very lucky person to do what
I do for a living.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
