<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers work quickly to repeal automatic mini-hike in gasoline tax </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The Assembly Appropriations Committee voted
Thursday to kill an automatic increase in taxes on gasoline before
it can take effect in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The increase would be so tiny as to be scarcely noticeable at
first, but lawmakers regarded the very idea of it to be annoying
and needless at a time when high gasoline prices are capturing
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats voted for the repeal unanimously, and
similar outcomes are expected next week in the full Assembly and in
the Senate. Gov. Christie Whitman has promised a quick signature.
</P>
<P>
   Now the only drama is time: The bill must get through both
houses in the next five working days in order to prevent the July 1
rate hike from taking effect.
</P>
<P>
   For most motorists, the rate hike would increase what they pay
for gasoline by only 1 cent on every 10 gallons of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   But because the tax is designed to collect 2.75 percent of
wholesale petroleum-product revenues, it could continue creeping
upward if the price of gas were to continue increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Should gasoline prices in New Jersey hit $2 a gallon, as they
have in the Chicago region, the increase would be 1.5 cents per
gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The tax increase has its root in a 1991 law creating a new tax
on wholesale petroleum products, everything from home heating oil
to engine lubricants, at a rate of 2.75 percent of gross receipts.
</P>
<P>
   To simplify calculating this tax for gasoline sales, the rate
was locked in at 4 cents per gallon provided that 4 cents remained
adequate to collect this minimum of 2.75 percent. When prices
dropped, the 4-cent rate did not drop along with them.
</P>
<P>
   ''They clearly intended it to be a floating thing. Of course, it
floated only up,'' said Assemblyman Richard Bagger, R-Union,
chairman of the Appropriations committee and sponsor of the bill,
A-2522, to repeal the tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   ''The price has dropped since 1991 and only now has exceeded
($1.44) again, so the built-in escalator in the 1991 law is now
relevant for the first time,'' Bagger said. ''It had sort of been
forgotten that was done 10 years ago and now it needs to be
adjusted before July 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said the obscure adjustment built into the 1991 law was
''a stealth tax increase.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll sign the repeal the minute it hits my desk, but it needs
to get here in a hurry,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bagger said he was pleased but puzzled by the governor's
enthusiasm because he said she could kill the tax increase
immediately by signing an executive order. ''We can't sign
executive orders in the Legislature, we can only pass bills,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The wholesale gasoline tax at issue is entirely separate from
the state's standard gasoline tax of 10.5 cents per gallon, which
is not being changed and would not be subject to any automatic
adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   --:
</P>
<P>
   Full text of A-2522 and other bills is available at the Office
of Legislative Services Web site located at
http://www.njleg.state.nj.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
