<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State appeals federal approval of New Jersey pipeline  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state Attorney General's Office on
Thursday filed an appeal challenging a federal decision to allow
expansion of a natural gas pipeline in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission in April approved a
plan to let Houston-based Transcontinental Gas Pipeline Corp. add
91 miles of pipeline in 10 New Jersey counties.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General John J. Farmer said Thursday that an appeal was
filed in the U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman said the state's argument will be, in
part, that the regulatory commission has failed to properly address
the safety of the proposed pipeline and failed to protect the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, U.S. Rep. Bill Pascrell Jr., D-N.J., filed a
petition with the U.S. Court of Appeals asking the court to review
the regulatory commission's approval.
</P>
<P>
   Transco maintains that the new pipelines are needed because
their existing network is at 100 percent of capacity and the
company anticipates the increased use of natural gas to fuel power
plants in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Transco says its extension would expand along the paths of
existing pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline would go through 31 municipalities in 10 New Jersey
counties - Bergen, Burlington, Essex, Hunterdon, Middlesex, Morris,
Passaic, Somerset, Union and Warren.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has generated local opposition. Homeowners,
environmental experts and politicians have said the project isn't
necessary, threatens wetlands and might pose a safety risk in
densely populated areas.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey officials have been wary of gas pipelines since a gas
explosion leveled much of an Edison apartment complex in 1994,
injuring more than 100 people and forcing 1,000 residents to flee.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer said that because of the specialized nature of federal
energy regulation, the Washington, D.C., law firm of Crowell &AMP;
Moring, which has experience on issues relating to the natural gas
regulatory process, will represent the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
