<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mixed verdict for ex-Atlantic City officer accused in videotaped beating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MAYS LANDING, N.J. (AP) - A former police officer caught on tape
beating a suspect was cleared in the beating Thursday but convicted
of lying about it.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas DiLorenzo, 33, was charged in the 1998 beating of a fan
at a Van Halen concert at Trump Marina Hotel Casino. Jack Hagopian,
21, of Havertown, Pa., was arrested after security guards saw him
light up a marijuana cigarette in the casino.
</P>
<P>
   The beating was captured on a black-and-white videotape made by
a surveillance camera in the casino holding cell where Hagopian was
taken by guards.
</P>
<P>
   On it, DiLorenzo could be seen punching, kicking and kneeing
Hagopian in the back as he and two guards struggled to handcuff the
6-foot-3-inch, 150-pound suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors called it excessive use of force; DiLorenzo said he
was defending himself and attempting to get Hagopian handcuffed so
the suspect couldn't hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   After 12 hours of deliberations over three days, a Superior
Court jury acquitted DiLorenzo of two counts of aggravated assault
and one count of official misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   He was convicted of filing a false police report, false swearing
and two counts of official misconduct. He could face 10 years in
prison. Superior Court Judge Manuel Greenberg set sentencing for
Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   DiLorenzo left court without comment. His lawyer, calling the
verdicts inconsistent, said an appeal would be filed.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Assistant Atlantic County Prosecutor James McClain called
the mixed verdict a victory for the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's definitely a victory. We're disappointed that the counts
relating to the assault didn't get favorable verdicts. But we're
pleased the jury recognized the accuracy of the other counts,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hagopian, who was not seriously hurt in the beating,
successfully sued the Police Department over it. He did not return
a telephone call seeking comment on the verdict Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 2110 </TRAILER>
