<HEADLINE> Report: Pilot Was On Medication  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- The pilot of a small plane that crashed on a
neighborhood street last year was taking medication for migraines
that should have kept him from flying, a federal report said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board investigators also said
that two of the plane's three gyroscopes, which help the pilot to
balance and direct the plane, weren't functioning.
</P>
<P>
   The Beechcraft Bonanza S35 crashed into a factory and barreled
down a Newark street, shedding its wings and tail before hitting a
restaurant Nov. 26. Pilot Itzhak Jacoby, 56, of Bethesda, Md., his
wife and daughter and one person on the ground were killed, and 25
people on the ground were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB report did not conclude whether the gyroscope problem
or Jacoby's use of Fiorinal caused the crash. A final report
listing a probable cause is expected within a month, NTSB
investigator David Muzio said.
</P>
<P>
   The report said Jacoby had taken Fiorinal, a migraine pain
medication that contains the sedative butalbital, since 1976 and
had a history of severe migraines. The FAA said Jacoby's
application for FAA medical certification did not list headache
problems or prescription medication for them.
</P>
<P>
   A history of chronic migraine or tension headaches would keep
pilots from flying, according to the FAA's 1999 guide for aviation
medical examiners.
</P>
<P>
   The headaches often need medication to cure, ''and in most
instances, the use of such medications is disqualifying because
they may interfere with a pilot's alertness and functioning,'' the
guidelines state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
