<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arthritis Drugs Tested Head-to-Head  </HEADLINE>
By PHIL GALEWITZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The results of the first head-to-head studies of
two blockbuster arthritis pain drugs -- paid for by the
pharmaceutical companies -- produced a split decision on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Merck &AMP; Co., which makes the arthritis drug Vioxx, said its pill
was better at reducing pain at night and during rest compared to
Pharmacia Corp.'s arthritis drug Celebrex.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacia countered that its studies found Vioxx was more likely
to increase high blood pressure and edema, a condition associated
with swelling in the legs. Pharmacia also said its studies found no
difference in how both drugs reduce pain.
</P>
<P>
   The companies presented the findings at a medical meeting in
Nice, France.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrex and Vioxx, both introduced last year in the United
States, are the first of a new class of painkillers to reduce pain
as well as older drugs but with the promise of less side effects
such as ulcers.
</P>
<P>
   Though Celebrex is slightly outselling Vioxx, both drugs are
expected to generate nearly $2 billion in sales in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The two drugmakers have been battling it out for the lucrative
pain drug market through heavy consumer advertising and sales calls
on doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, all the studies released on the two drugs involved
tests against placebo or older anti-inflammatory medicines.
Drugmakers rarely conduct head-to-head studies comparing their drug
to rivals because of the risk of a bad outcome.
</P>
<P>
   It unclear if the latest studies will have much of an impact on
doctor's prescribing habits, said pharmaceutical analyst Hemant
Shah of HKS &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   He said the two companies may actually be hurting themselves by
doing studies revealing faults with each other's drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Shah said the companies need to focus on showing how the drugs
are substantially better than ibuprofen and other older drugs,
which cost considerably less than the $2.42 for the daily dosage of
Celebrex and Vioxx.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ted Fields, a rheumatologist at the Hospital for Special
Surgery in New York, said earlier studies show Vioxx and Celebrex
are better than older medicines, but there's no major difference
between the two new brands. Doctors will pay close attention to
these new studies, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The studies conducted by Merck and Pharmacia each asked test
subjects to rate how well they felt after taking Celebrex or Vioxx.
</P>
<P>
   The Pharmacia study of 800 patients with osteoarthritis and high
blood pressure found that 12 percent of Vioxx patients and 6
percent of Celebrex patients developed higher blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The six-week study also found 10 percent of patients taking
Vioxx experienced edema, swelling in the legs, compared to 5
percent taking Celebrex.
</P>
<P>
   In a second Pharmacia study of 182 patients taking Celebrex and
Vioxx, investigators found no difference in how the two brand drugs
relieve pain.
</P>
<P>
   Merck's six-week study of 382 arthritis patients also found in
most measurements the drugs worked equally as well at relieving
pain. But Merck said its study found more subjects rated Vioxx
better at relieving pain during the night and during rest.
</P>
<P>
   The Merck study also found no difference between the drugs in
relieving morning stiffness or pain walking on a flat surface.
</P>
<P>
   In trading Thursday, shares of Merck fell 93.75 cents to $71.50,
and Pharmacia slipped $3.25 to $52.125, both on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.vioxx.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.celebrex.com
</P>
</TEXT>
