<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expos Release Veteran Catcher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Catcher Charlie O'Brien was released Thursday by
the Montreal Expos, who activated Lenny Webster from the 15-day
disabled list,
</P>
<P>
   In another move, Montreal optioned rookie Brian Schneider to
Triple-A Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a lot of conversations about the whole thing,'' Expos
general manager Jim Beattie said. ''It was not necessarily a slam
dunk because Charlie's been a good addition to us since spring
training. It was difficult but I felt like this would be the best
combination for us.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, a spring training invitee who was with Anaheim last
year but missed most of the season due to a foot injury, re-injured
his right arch while running out a homer during spring training and
missed the beginning of this season.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, 39, went 1-for-3 Wednesday night in his first start for
Montreal since June 7. He hit .211 in nine games for the Expos
after his contract was purchased from Double-A Harrisburg on May
25.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't been playing in the last couple of weeks,'' O'Brien
said. ''It's one of those things where you deal with it, and go on.
I'm not going to play just to play anymore. If I can go help a team
that might have a chance to win, then yeah, I would. But otherwise,
it's time to go home and be a dad.''
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed-hitting Schneider, 23, batted .273 in 17 games
for Montreal, including eight starts. He made his major league
debut for the Expos on May 26 in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Widger, the Expos' starting catcher, is hitting .237 with
eight homers and 19 RBIs in 50 games.
</P>
<P>
   Webster, placed on the 15-day DL on June 7 due to tendinitis in
his right shoulder, is hitting .216 in 16 games, including nine
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We decided that we wanted to go with two catchers and felt
like this would be the better combination for us right now,''
Beattie said. ''It allows us some flexibility, with Brian catching
in Triple-A, if Widger were to get hurt, or Lenny were to get hurt.
It allowed us to get a bat on the bench that we think we've been
missing.
</P>
</TEXT>
