<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts: Sports Violence Continues  </HEADLINE>
By CADONNA M. PEYTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- It's happened for decades -- sports fans
turning the celebration of a big win or a hometown championship
into a violent free-for-all.
</P>
<P>
   It happened in Detroit in 1968, 1984 and 1990. It happened in
Pittsburgh in 1971, Montreal in 1986 and repeatedly last decade in
Chicago and Denver. It happened again Monday night in Los Angeles
when fans celebrating the Lakers' NBA championship burned police
cars, thrashed television news vans, set bonfires and caused
extensive damage to downtown businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say such outbursts can be expected for decades to come.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're always going to have some of these breakdowns,'' said
Demetrius Piarson, professor in the Department of Health and Human
Performance at the University of Houston. ''Some of these
individuals have much at stake. They identify with these teams.
They've grown up with these teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Fan analysts and sports psychologists call them the
''overidentified fans,'' people who feel so strongly about a team
that they consider themselves a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   When hundreds of such fanatics get together, celebrations can
get out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are more prone to do deviant acts when they are in a
group,'' Piarson said.
</P>
<P>
   Violent behavior following a big game is a well-worn phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, police arrested 200 people after the Detroit Tigers won
the World Series. Fans smashed store windows and set fires. One
woman was raped.
</P>
<P>
   It only got worse in the Motor City in 1984 when 100,000 fans
poured into the streets after the Tigers won the World Series,
destroying police cars and taxi cabs, setting some on fire. Dozens
were arrested, many were injured and one person was killed. Six
years later, after the Pistons won their second straight NBA
championship, seven people were killed, six of them hit by cars,
and hundreds were hurt by gunfire, stabbings and fighting as
widespread looting broke out.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of hockey fans took over the streets of Montreal after
the Canadiens won their 23rd Stanley Cup in 1986. Police finally
gained control after an estimated $2 million in damage.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, one man was killed and a child blinded during the
violence that followed the Chicago Bulls' fifth NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   Fans in Denver rioted following the Broncos' Super Bowl
victories in 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1998 melee, Denver officials prepared for the
following year's Super Bowl by increasing the downtown police
presence. They also restricted parking and blocked major roads to
discourage crowds.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help. Fans set fires, broke windows and threw bottles
at police, causing an estimated $160,000 in damage after the team's
championship repeat.
</P>
<P>
   The aftermath was like ''following the path of a hurricane,''
said Andrew Hudson, spokesman for Denver Mayor Wellington Webb.
</P>
<P>
   ''Psychologists define it as the excitement of winning a major
championship, coupled with testosterone and booze. I wish it was
that simple,'' he said. ''Folks who wouldn't think they would
normally get caught up in this are out there throwing rocks at
police officers. It's a totally bizarre thing.''
</P>
<P>
   All the more puzzling is why some cities suffer such outbursts
while others celebrate peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' win Monday is the nation's third major professional
sports championship this year, but the only one to turn violent.
</P>
<P>
   After the New Jersey Devils won the Stanley Cup this month, the
most serious incident was fans booing Gov. Christie Whitman when
she appeared days later at the victory celebration.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis fans were raucous but peaceful during the Rams' march
to a Super Bowl victory in January.
</P>
<P>
   After the team's win in the conference championship, fans danced
and sang in the streets, high-fiving with motorcycle police. That
picture stands in stark contrast to the images that dominated
television footage in the hours after the Lakers' win, when young
rioters jumped on empty patrol cars, kicked in their windows and
set them ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   Those who study societal trends, however, say post-game violence
can happen anywhere and is sure to happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have created a culture of violence in which it seems
acceptable for emotions to be expressed in a violent manner,'' said
the Rev. C. Welton Gaddy, executive director of The Interfaith
Alliance, a Washington, D.C.-based nonprofit that represents
various religious faiths.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, people conditioned by that culture are apt to
express their joy through destructive behavior...''
</P>
<P>
   Gaddy said politicians, sports players and others who are role
models need to help ''build a societal intolerance to incivility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-22-00 2127 </TRAILER>
