<HEADLINE> Notes on Thursday's Baseball Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Tigers-Blue Jays:
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT: Juan Gonzalez, the subject of trade rumors, was the DH
against Toronto. ... The Tigers scored 18 runs Tuesday night, but
were shut out Wednesday. Detroit is 1-7 in games following
double-digit runs.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: RHP Roy Halladay, demoted to the minors on May 16, will
be recalled Saturday and pitch against the Red Sox. ... The Blue
Jays activated C Todd Greene from the 15-day disabled list. To make
room, they demoted C Josh Phelps to Double A Tennessee. ... Carlos
Delgado extended his hitting streak to 16 games.
Yankees-Red Sox:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Jake Westbrook didn't last much longer in his second
major league start than he did in his first. He was charged with
four runs on six hits and two walks in 2 2-3 innings. On Saturday,
he gave up six runs in 1 2-3 innings against the Chicago White Sox.
... Bernie Williams has homered in three consecutive games. ... 2B
Chuck Knoblauch made another throwing error -- his fifth in eight
games, throwing wide of first base in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: Nomar Garciaparra had a pair of doubles in the first
three innings to raise his batting average above .400. He has hit
in 12 consecutive games. ... The Red Sox recalled RHP John Wasdin
from Triple-A Pawtucket to pitch Friday night against Toronto in
place of Jeff Fassero, who went on the disabled list. ... Jeff Frye
has hit in 27 of 29 games.
Indians-White Sox:
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: General manager John Hart said OF Manny Ramirez could
be out another three weeks after reinjuring his left hamstring
during a rehab assignment last weekend with Double-A Akron. Manager
Charlie Manuel said Ramirez worked out in Cleveland on Thursday and
was told he was doing better. ... RHP Charles Nagy, who underwent
right elbow surgery on May 19, is scheduled to make his second
rehab start Monday. If everything goes well, he could rejoin the
team next week, Manuel said. ... Before hitting a triple, double
and single against the White Sox on Wednesday night, Kenny Lofton
and teammate Russell Branyan tussled over a clubhouse card game and
had to be separated.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: CF Chris Singleton was rested and out of the starting
lineup Thursday night, despite an eight-game hitting streak. Jeff
Abbott got the start. ... First base coach Bryan Little presented
the starting lineups at home plate, exchanging them with his
brother Grady, the Indians' bench coach. ... For a fourth straight
game, the crowd greeted the White Sox with a standing ovation as
they took the field. ... RHP Jon Garland, regarded as the White
Sox's top minor league pitching prospect, was chosen to play in the
Triple-A All-Star game. Garland, who has eight wins, was acquired
from the Cubs two years ago for reliever Matt Karchner. The
6-foot-6 Garland was the 10th overall pick in the 1997 draft.
Twins-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: Twins 3B Ron Coomer made his first start Thursday
since corrective surgery on his right foot. Coomer had two tendons
cut in his foot during a surgical procedure after Sunday's game. He
missed two starts but came on as a pinch-hitter in the eighth
inning of Wednesday's 7-5 loss to the Rangers. Coomer flew out for
the third out with two runners on base. ... Twins CEO Chris Clouser
was in Arlington, Texas, and attended the game. ... SS Cristian
Guzman hit his major league-leading 12th triple Wednesday. He is on
pace for 27 triples this year. Rod Carew holds the Twins' record
for triples in a season with 16.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: Rangers RHP John Wetteland was not injured Wednesday
night when hit on the ankle by a ball hit by Twins OF Matt Lawton
in the ninth inning. ''He's OK,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ''He
said he's ready to pitch.'' ... Former Rangers OF Ruben Sierra will
play in the Triple-A All-Star Game on July 12 in Rochester, N.Y.,
and is hitting .332 with seven homers and 35 RBIs for the Oklahoma
RedHawks. He played in three major league All-Star Games (1989,
'91, '92) for the Rangers.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Pirates-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: Both teams had to skip batting practice as a
violent, late afternoon thunderstorm knocked out power in the area
surrounding Olympic Stadium. The stadium's lights were restored one
hour and 20 minutes prior to game time. ... OF John Vander Wal's
second grand slam of the season in Wednesday's 8-3 win made him the
first Pirate with more than one grand slam in the same season since
Jeff King hit three in 1996. ... Pittsburgh starters have allowed
just four earned runs in 24 1-3 innings of their last four starts
for a 1.48 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: With C Lenny Webster activated from the 15-day
disabled list Thursday, the Expos elected to go with just two
catchers, releasing veteran Charlie O'Brien and optioning
left-handed hitting rookie Brian Schneider to Triple-A Ottawa.
1B-OF Fernando Seguignol was recalled from the Lynx, giving
Montreal a switch-hitter with power off the bench. ... Injured
closer Ugueth Urbina threw off the mound for five minutes and will
continue to throw in preparation for a rehab assignment with
Ottawa, beginning July 3. RHP Mike Thurman, currently on the 15-day
disabled list for the second time this season with right elbow
tendinitis, also threw off the mound Thursday and will throw again
Sunday, before joining Ottawa on July 4 for his rehab assignment.
... LF Rondell White rejoined the lineup after missing the first
three games of the series with a sore left knee.
Cubs-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: The Cubs had won six of their previous eight games at
Turner Field. ... Sammy Sosa collected his 1500th career hit in the
fifth inning. ... Glenallen Hill is batting .478 off Terry
Mulholland after going 2-for-4. ... Eric Young was charged with his
eighth error, fourth-most among NL second basemen.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Chipper Jones' hitting streak ended at 19 games. He was
robbed of a potential three-run homer in the fourth inning when
Damon Buford made an above-the-fence catch in center. ... Terry
Mulholland won for the fourth time in six starts.
Brewers-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: The Brewers three home runs' Wednesday hit by Marquis
Grissom, Jeromy Burnitz and Tyler Houston tied a season-high for
most homers in a game this season, accomplished for the fifth time.
... Brewers RHP Jason Bere will make his first appearance against
Atlanta on Friday. He's 2-3 with a 5.28 ERA in five starts against
NL East teams this season.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Marlins manager John Boles gave three of his starters
the night off, barring late-game substitutions. David Berg started
in place of Luis Castillo at second; Mark Smith played left instead
of Cliff Floyd, and Andy Fox was at shortstop in place of Alex
Gonzalez. ... The Marlins have allowed three runs or less in seven
of nine games. ... Marlins RHP Ryan Dempster has a 2.06 ERA at
home, fifth in the majors behind Randy Johnson, Kevin Brown, Shawn
Estes and Pedro Martinez.
Rockies-Reds:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: After concluding their series with the Reds on
Thursday, the Rockies head for Arizona and a weekend series that
will decide first place in the NL West. ... Starter Kevin Jarvis, a
1991 Reds draft pick, made his first career appearance against
Cincinnati on Thursday. It was his 50th career start. ... In his
first five games against the Reds this season, Larry Walker went
10-for-20.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: The Reds moved OF Deion Sanders from the disabled
list to a restricted list, maintaining their rights to him. Sanders
ended his baseball career again to play football for the Washington
Redskins. ... LHP Ron Villone, scratched from Thursday's game
because of a cut on his left index finger, said he hurt himself at
home a few days ago. He can throw without problem, but the cut
bleeds when he throws a fastball. He hopes to make his next start.
Phillies-Mets:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: Rookie 1B Pat Burrell, the No. 1 pick in the 1998
draft, is beginning to show why he was so heralded as a college
hitter at Miami. Burrell is 8-for-26 in seven games, including his
first multihomer game and first grand slam in Wednesday night's
victory. Since being recalled May 24, he's hitting .221 (21-for-95)
with six homers and 19 RBIs. ''He's only gotten about 90 at-bats or
so, but you've seen glimpses of the type of player he's going to
be,'' Phillies manager Terry Francona said. ''He's still developing
and he wants to get better. It's real easy to be patient with a
player like that.'' ... 1B Rico Brogna, on the DL since May 11 with
a broken left forearm, participated in light outfield drills before
the game -- with the cast on. He said he hopes to return by the
All-Star break. ... A win on Thursday night would give the Phillies
a season-high four-game winning streak, and their first road sweep
of the season. ... RHP Robert Person is skipping his scheduled
start Friday with tightness in his shoulder. RHP Dave Coggin, who
will be recalled from Triple-A Scranton Wilkes-Barre on Friday,
will make his major league debut against Montreal in Person's
place.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: As GM Steve Phillips spoke to the media before the
game, fans chanted ''A-Rod! A-Rod!'' for Alex Rodriguez, the highly
coveted Seattle SS who will be a free agent after this season.
Since the Mets learned SS Rey Ordonez will be out the rest of the
season with a broken arm, Rodriguez has gone to the top of many
fans' wish lists. ''I can understand why the fans get excited about
him,'' Phillips said. ''He's a great player, but from our
standpoint, I can't comment on another player from another team
because that's tampering.'' ... RHP Bobby J. Jones will be recalled
from Triple-A Norfolk on Friday to start against Pittsburgh. Jones
was 1-3 with a 10.91 ERA before being sent down. ... The Mets play
14 of their next 18 games at Shea Stadium. ... The Mets have hit 20
home runs in 11 games.
Dodgers-Astros:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: Matt Herges is the first Dodgers pitcher to start
5-0 since Antonio Osuna did it in 1998. Herges ranked second among
NL rookies in wins, and is first among rookie relievers with 40
strikeouts. ... C-INF Jim Leyritz was in uniform for the first time
Thursday after being traded from the Yankees for Jose Vizcaino on
Tuesday.
</P>
