   HOUSTON: Craig Biggio needs three hits to pass Jose Cruz as the
Astros' career hits leader. Biggio has 1,935 hits. ... Jeff Bagwell
is the only Astros opening day starter who has not missed time due
to either injury or illness this season. Bagwell and Biggio were
the only opening day starters last season not to spend at least
some time on the DL. Biggio hasn't ever been on the DL in his
career, but missed two games early this season with an eye problem.
Giants-Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: OF Ellis Burks sat out with knee soreness.
Manager Dusty Baker said he'd be happy if Burks could play two out
of every three days. ... Baker isn't looking forward to the Giants'
first trip to Enron Field for a three-game series against the
Astros from Friday through Sunday. He didn't think the flag pole in
center field, the weird angles and the concrete curb in the
outfield were cute touches. ''You're going to hurt some high-priced
players,'' Baker said. ''Is it worth the risk? Some of the guys
haven't played there to know the hazards.'' ... After a 90-minute
meeting with struggling RHP Russ Ortiz and pitching coach Dave
Righetti, Baker decided not to demote Ortiz to the bullpen. Ortiz,
an 18-game winner last year, but 3-7 with a 6.89 ERA this year,
will start Sunday at Houston. ''I think it's hard to work it out
when you're out of the rotation,'' Baker said. ''He's where Shawn
Estes was a little while ago, where he's a little confused between
power and finesse, which happens to guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Manager Tony La Russa wasn't blaming C Mike Matheny
for trying to bunt for a hit in the seventh inning of Wednesday's
4-1 loss to the Giants. Matheny, the No. 8 hitter, ended up with a
sacrifice, and La Russa allowed pitcher Garrett Stephenson to bat
with two outs and a runner on second. La Russa said Matheny told
him that he noticed the defense was playing well back. ''It's not a
bad play on his part,'' La Russa said. ''He gets the ball past the
pitcher, it's a hit.'' ... 3B Fernando Tatis, on the disabled list
since April 29 with a torn groin, will hit in simulated game action
for the second time Friday with reliever David Wainhouse -- also on
the disabled list -- doing the throwing. On Wednesday, Wainhouse was
wild and Tatis only took a couple of swings, but La Russa said it
still was a good barometer because Tatis was able to sight the ball
and lay off bad pitches. The team remained undecided whether to
activate Tatis whenever he's ready and let him play in the majors,
or send him on a brief rehab assignment. ... Shawon Dunston batted
leadoff for the first time this season Thursday. ''I'm not looking
for a walk,'' the free-swinging Dunston said before the game. ''See
ball, hit ball, have some fun.'' Last year, Dunston walked twice in
106 plate appearances.
</P>
