<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Board votes to raise rental units  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - The city's Rent Guidelines Board voted Thursday
to let landlords increase rent on one-and two-year leases,
affecting 1 million rent-stabilized apartments.
</P>
<P>
   The board approved a 4 percent increase for one-year leases and
6 percent for two-year leases, the largest increase in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Neither tenant groups nor landlord advocates have been happy
with the board's proposals in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Some tenants - carrying signs and chanting ''shame, shame,'' -
stormed the stage Thursday and briefly interrupted the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   A police spokesman did not immediately know whether any arrests
were made.
</P>
<P>
   Landlord advocates had wanted rent hikes of 9 percent on
one-year leases and 15 percent on two-year leases. They've said the
hikes were needed to offset rising operating costs, particularly
fuel oil, and to recoup from the recession.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani called the board's decision
''unfortunate'' but pointed out that the panel is independent of
his administration. He had urged the board to approve increases of
3 percent for one-year leases and 5 percent for two-year leases.
</P>
<P>
   He also blamed President Clinton for allowing heating oil prices
to soar.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly, some of the pressure exerted on the board was due to
the fact that there appears to be no relief in sight from the
ever-increasing price of home heating oil resulting from OPEC's
price gouging,'' Giuliani said in a press release. ''This has been
going on for over a year without any adequate response from the
Clinton administration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 2140 </TRAILER>
