<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressMichel Droit
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Michel Droit, a prize-winning French novelist,
journalist and one of 40 members of the prestigious Academie
Francaise, died Thursday. No cause of death was given. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   A novelist, essayist and editorialist for two decades with the
conservative daily Le Figaro, Droit gained wide acclaim for his
interviews with Gen. Charles de Gaulle.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, he was elected to the Academie Francaise -- one of only
40 ''immortals'' as the institution's members are known.
</P>
<P>
   He worked in radio and television, and was the only journalist
in France to interview de Gaulle on television -- in December 1965,
June 1968 and April 1969, a year before the general's death in
1970.
</P>
<P>
   Droit's professional career was intricately linked to de
Gaulle's. In 1972, Droit won the Edmond-Michelet prize for ''A Free
Frenchman,'' a documentary about de Gaulle, France's most
influential postwar leader.
</P>
<P>
   His five-volume ''Man of Destiny'' is widely regarded as one of
the most thorough examinations of de Gaulle's life and work.
</P>
<P>
   Editor in chief at France's state-run television in the early
1960s, Droit launched several successful programs, including ''A
Propos,'' which ran for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Droit worked at Le Figaro's literary supplement from 1961-71,
and went on to write columns for the weekly Figaro Magazine. In
1984, he published four volumes of his private diary, and later,
two volumes of memoirs.
Jim Hensley
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Jim Hensley, father of Sen. John McCain's wife
and the founder of the nation's second-largest Anheuser-Busch
distributorship, died Wednesday after a lengthy illness. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   Hensley, a World War II veteran, was the founder, owner and
chairman of the board of Hensley &AMP; Co., which accounted for much of
the family's wealth.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Cindy Hensley McCain, was married in 1980 to
McCain, Arizona's senior senator who pushed presumptive GOP
presidential nominee George W. Bush in this year's presidential
primaries before bowing out.
Wallace Savage
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Former Dallas Mayor Wallace Savage, who is
credited with preserving one of the city's best-known historic
areas and bringing racial equality to some of the city's services,
died Monday after a stroke and battle with pneumonia. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   Savage served as mayor from 1949 to 1951. He and his wife worked
to save homes from being razed and replaced with apartments.
Community leaders in Dallas credited the couple with starting a
movement that led to city preservation ordinances.
</P>
<P>
   Savage, who was elected mayor when segregation was the norm,
crusaded against violence against blacks, eliminated the city's
segregated ambulance service and made city parks accessible to
blacks. He also refused to bow to pressure from white leaders who
wanted to deny police protection to blacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-22-00 2151 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
