<HEADLINE> Diver Troy Dumais Hospitalized  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   FEDERAL WAY, Wash. (AP) -- Troy Dumais, who was second heading
into Thursday's night 3-meter springboard finals at the U.S.
Olympic diving trials, twice visited a hospital earlier in the day
because of kidney stones.
</P>
<P>
   Dumais, 21, arrived at King County Aquatic Center about 1&AMP;frac12; hours
before the competition began and planned to dive, his coach Matt
Scoggin said. He didn't appear to be in visible pain during several
minutes of practice.
</P>
<P>
   Dumais, who passed a kidney stone last July during the World
University Games in Spain, went to St. Francis Hospital with pain
in his left side at 2 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He was given an anti-inflammatory medicine that didn't contain
banned steroids rather than a commonly used morphine-based
medication, Scoggin said. Dumais immediately felt better and left
the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   However, the pain returned shortly before 5 p.m. and Dumais
returned to the hospital for another shot of medicine and a liter
of fluid, Scoggin said.
</P>
<P>
   Dumais didn't pass a kidney stone, but Scoggin said there was
significant blood in the diver's urine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
