<DOCNO> APW20000622.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, June 22, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Texas Inmate Gary Graham Executed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- Gary Graham, subject of the most contentious Texas
death penalty case since Gov. George W. Bush began running for president, was
executed tonight for a 1981 murder he said he did not commit. Graham, 36,
received a lethal injection for the killing of a man in a holdup outside a
Houston supermarket. The state parole board and appeals courts rejected his
arguments that he was convicted on shaky evidence from a single eyewitness and
that his trial lawyer did a poor job.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Probe Is Urged
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Government officials today confirmed that the most recent
prosecutor to question Al Gore about his 1996 fund raising is recommending a
special counsel investigate whether the vice president lied. Thursday brought
other menacing news for Democrats. Independent Counsel Robert Ray reported
''substantial evidence'' Hillary Rodham Clinton played a role in White House
travel office firings, contrary to her denials, but said he would not bring
charges against her.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Prosecutor Cites Clinton Travel Role
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Independent Counsel Robert Ray said today that, despite
her denials, there is ''substantial evidence'' that Hillary Rodham Clinton
played a role in White House travel office firings, but the prosecutor said he
won't bring charges because there's not enough evidence to convict the first
lady. The announcement comes less than six months before the 2000 election. Mrs.
Clinton is seeking to become a U.S. senator from New York.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senate Nixes Worker Protections
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Republican-controlled Senate voted tonight to block
proposed Clinton administration rules giving workers new protections against
repetitive motion injuries. The 57-41 vote was mostly along party lines, and
came several days after the House adopted a similar ban. Democrats said the
regulations developed by the Occupational Safety and Health Administration could
help an estimated 1.8 million workers who suffer from ergonomic injuries each
year. Republicans insisted that the new rules would cost businesses too much.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dutch Trucker Charged in 58 Deaths
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Prosecutors on Thursday charged a Dutch truck driver with 58
counts of manslaughter after a group of illegal Chinese immigrants suffocated in
his vehicle, police said. Perry Wacker, the first person to be charged in the
case, has been held since Sunday, when authorities said they discovered the
bodies of the victims and two survivors in an airtight compartment of his truck.
Police said they found the 60 illegal Chinese after the truck arrived at the
English Channel port of Dover made a five-hour ferry crossing from Zeebrugge,
Belgium.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Congress Leaders OK Spending Pact
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House and Senate leaders broke a spending impasse today,
agreeing to free $12 billion in long-delayed funds to help Colombia's war on
drugs, pay for U.S. troops in Kosovo and provide natural disaster relief. The
agreement came as the Senate voted 95-4 to endorse a $13.4 billion foreign aid
bill. The legislation contained just under $1 billion in anti-narcotics
assistance to Colombia. However, under the new agreement that amount will now be
increased to $1.3 billion.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Canada Rejects Olestra
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- A fat substitute used in popular snack foods was rejected
by a Canadian food regulatory agency, making the United States the only country
to approve olestra as a food ingredient. Olestra is used in Frito-Lay Inc.'s
Wow! chips, Procter &AMP; Gamble Co.'s Pringles chips and other foods. Health
Canada's food regulatory agency, which said P&AMP;G did not adequately support its
claim that adding vitamins to foods containing olestra counteracts the fat
substitute's tendency to inhibit the body's absorption of some nutrients.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nasdaq Ends Down 127, Dow Falls 122
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq ran out of gas today, cutting short a
five-session winning streak that had brought the average above one important
milestone -- 4,000 points -- and nearly above another, where it began the year.
The Nasdaq composite index fell 127.17 to 3,936.84. The damage was less severe
in the Dow Jones industrial average, which fell 121.62 to close at 10,376.12. On
the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,863-999.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McGwire Ties Schmidt's Homer Mark
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Mark McGwire tied Mike Schmidt for seventh on the career
home run list, hitting No. 548 in the fourth inning against the San Francisco
Giants tonight. McGwire's first homer in three days was the Cardinals' first hit
off Shawn Estes. It came on a 2-0 pitch, and traveled an estimated 475 feet to
straightaway center. McGwire has 101 homers and 214 RBIs in 212 career games at
Busch Stadium.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
