<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympics Organizer Usher Dies  </HEADLINE>
By ERICA WERNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Harry Usher, Peter Ueberroth's right-hand man
in organizing the 1984 Olympics in Los Angeles, died Thursday of an
apparent heart attack. He was 61.
</P>
<P>
   Usher was found dead at 7:25 a.m. in a workout room in a
Secaucus, N.J., hotel. The Los Angeles resident had been commuting
to New Jersey, where he ran an Internet sports company.
</P>
<P>
   Usher was an attorney whose career ranged far from the practice
of entertainment law, his specialty. He was the second and last
commissioner of the upstart United States Football League during
its unsuccessful challenge of the National Football League in the
1980s and also served as executive director of the Association of
Volleyball Professionals.
</P>
<P>
   But his most prominent role was as executive vice president and
general manager of the Los Angeles Olympic Organizing Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney's clients included Ueberroth, and the millionaire
entrepreneur and former baseball commissioner tapped him for the
role.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of unprofitable Olympic Games, the two were given
what many said was an impossible task, organizing the first
privately funded Olympics. They not only raised the money needed,
but ended up with a stunning $225 million surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a brilliant man,'' said Anita DeFrantz, president of
the Amateur Athletic Foundation of Los Angeles, which is funded by
the surplus. ''His gift to the Olympic movement was his
extraordinary management of the 1984 Olympic Games. And he
certainly will be remembered for his enormous skills as a
manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Usher helped put together an Olympics in a city so
geographically spread out and lacking in public transportation that
many believed freeways would shut down in gridlock when sports
events began taking place at venues as far as 50 miles apart. But
after a massive campaign that publicized event times, parking and
alternative routes, the games took place in a city that residents
would later say seemed less crowded than normal.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 10 years later, Ueberroth came to Usher for help again,
this time making him his second-in-command at Rebuild LA, the
nonprofit group charged with rebuilding the city after the 1992
riots.
</P>
<P>
   Usher's latest venture was the Internet sports company
PROTEAM.com, which DeFrantz said he was in the process of
relocating from the East Coast to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey native is survived by his wife, Jane, and six
children from two marriages.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service will be held Sunday at the offices of the
Amateur Athletic Foundation in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-22-00 2207 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000622.0229 </DOCNO>
