<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brewers 6, Marlins 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- John Snyder pitched two-hit shutout ball over six
innings, and Charlie Hayes hit a two-run homer, leading the
Milwaukee Brewers to a 6-1 victory over the Florida Marlins on
Thursday night and a split of the four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder (3-2), who has won his last three starts, gave up just
two singles. He struck out four and walked six.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Lopez hit a solo homer in the first and Hayes, who ended an
0-for-20 skid Wednesday, ripped a two-run homer over the left-field
scoreboard in the fourth for a 3-0 lead. Lopez singled and scored
ahead of Hayes' sixth homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Jenkins, a seventh-inning defensive replacement in left
field, hit his 13th homer, a solo shot, leading off the eighth
against reliever Vic Darensbourg. It was the second consecutive
night the Brewers hit three homers.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Blanco's two-run double in the ninth capped the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Sanchez (4-6), who has five losses and three no-decisions
in his last eight starts, gave up six hits and three runs in 6 1-3
innings, with seven strikeouts and one walk.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder got out of a bases-loaded, one-out jam in the fourth by
striking out Andy Fox and Paul Bako.
</P>
<P>
   Bako hit a one-out single in the seventh off reliever Juan
Acevedo and scored on Mark Kotsay's two-out triple for the Marlins'
lone run.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Brewers RHP Jason Bere will make his first appearance
against Atlanta on Friday. He's 2-3 with a 5.28 ERA in five starts
against NL East teams this season. ... Sanchez gave up two homers,
giving him a team-high 18, tied for fourth-most in the NL. ...
Marlins manager John Boles gave three starters the night off. David
Berg started in place of Luis Castillo at second; Mark Smith played
left instead of Cliff Floyd, and Fox was at shortstop in place of
Alex Gonzalez. Floyd flied out as a pinch-hitter in the seventh ...
The Marlins drew 8,285 fans, their highest attendance figure in the
four-game series.
</P>
</TEXT>
