<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tests Artillery Near Taiwan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- China on Friday began live-fire artillery
tests off its southeast coast directly across from Taiwan, Taiwan's
military said.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwanese officials said the exercises were routine and not a
threat to this island.
</P>
<P>
   The tests will continue through Friday at Fujian Province's
Quanzhou Bay and Shenlu Bay, the Defense Ministry said in a
statement that did not cite its sources.
</P>
<P>
   The Taiwanese military closely monitors China, the island's
biggest military threat.
</P>
<P>
   Defense officials are cautious about what kind of information is
released. In the past, news about Chinese military movements have
caused the Taiwanese stock market to plunge.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, China has conducted similar tests off Fujian's
coast, about 190 miles west of northern Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   China and Taiwan have been governed separately since the two
sides split amid civil war in 1949. While Taiwan has dismissed the
artillery drills as routine, China has not wavered in its threats
to reunify with the island -- by force if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   China distrusts Taiwanese President Chen Shui-bian, who was once
a vocal supporter of Taiwan independence. However, before his March
election victory, Chen softened his stance, saying he would only
put the independence issue to an island-wide vote if China attacks.
</P>
<P>
   China has in the past used its military to cause tension during
times of political change in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   When Taiwan held its first direct presidential election in 1996,
China tested nuclear-capable missiles near the island's two main
ports, prompting the United States to send warships to the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-22-00 2217 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000622.0237 </DOCNO>
