<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Elections Set  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS HAWLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela's presidential election --
postponed once because of technical problems -- will be held on July
30, lawmakers said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislative Commission also approved that date for the
election of governors, legislators and mayors and set Oct. 1 for
election of regional and local councils.
</P>
<P>
   The elections, aimed at overhauling Venezuela's government and
give life to its new constitution, were originally scheduled for
May 28. But the Supreme Court postponed them because of technical
problems including the omission of some candidates from a database
needed to count votes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is time to get on with these elections,'' commission
president Luis Miquilena said after the vote Thursday night. ''It
is time to get out of this transitory period even if we have to
break the elections in two parts.''
</P>
<P>
   The elections are a crucial part of President Hugo Chavez's
makeover of the Venezuelan government. Every public office in the
country -- more than 6,200 positions -- is up for grabs, making it
the biggest election in Venezuelan history. More than 36,000
candidates will participate.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's allies see the vote as a chance to sweep away a
political system that for decades failed to solve Venezuelans'
poverty despite the country's oil riches.
</P>
<P>
   His opponents fear Chavez -- who led a failed coup in 1992 before
his election in 1998 -- is trying to establish an authoritarian
state.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an assembly packed with Chavez allies rewrote the
constitution to give broad powers to the president. It then
dissolved the 227-seat Congress and appointed the 21-member
Legislative Commision, a temporary legislature also dominated by
Chavez supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders had wanted all of the elections on the same
date. They feared that if Chavez wins the presidency as expected,
his victory would give momentum to other candidates of his Fifth
Republic Movement party.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the country's National Electoral Council said a
single election date would overwhelm ballot counters and urged
lawmakers to split them up.
</P>
<P>
   ''The (elections) couldn't be done all together in the short
term, as the country had demanded,'' said Elias Jaua, second vice
president of the Legislative Assembly. ''For that reason, it was
more prudent and sensible to divide the elections.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
