<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colorado Wildfires Nearly Contained  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Fires that burned 21,000 acres in Colorado's
foothills were close to being controlled Thursday, although crews
continued to monitor hot spots and watch for flare-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters also were on standby in Grand Junction, Pueblo and
Durango in case any new wildfires erupted.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-nine of Colorado's 63 counties had fire restrictions
Thursday because of the dry conditions that helped fuel the fires
southwest of Denver and east of Rocky Mountain National Park.
</P>
<P>
   The fire 35 miles southwest of Denver scorched about 10,800
acres and burned 51 homes and a sawmill. More than 400 firefighters
remained on the lines guarding against flare-ups.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 firefighters were at the fire east of Rocky Mountain
National Park, which burned 10,600 acres and 22 structures.
</P>
<P>
   Both fires were contained, meaning lines dug around them were
holding, U.S. Forest Service spokesman Lynn Young said. It might be
several days before the blazes are considered controlled, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Both fires started June 12 and spread quickly in the windy,
bone-dry foothills. Authorities first thought lightning may have
started the fires but now believe one of them may have been caused
by a campfire.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of fighting both fires totaled $7.4 million, the
National Interagency Fire Center's Web site said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Interagency Fire Center: http://www.nifc.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
