<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers vote Jet Ski regulations; emissions standards  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state Legislature passed bills on
Thursday to cut emissions from ''Jet Skis'' and to allow
municipalities to limit or ban their use on waterways across New
York state.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the measures say the increasingly popular personal
watercraft - ''Jet Ski'' is a trademarked name - have become a
noisy nuisance to other boaters and swimmers on some lakes and
rivers. They can also be a danger to their riders if operated
improperly, and environmentalists say they generate too much
pollution and threaten shoreline wildlife habitats when they are
operated in very shallow water.
</P>
<P>
   ''New York's recreational assets and environment should not be
subjugated to the joy-riding whims of a few thrill seekers,'' said
David Higby of Environmental Advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Giving local governments the power to regulate ''Jet Ski'' usage
is the fairest and quickest way to introduce limits statewide,
according to state Assemblyman Thomas DiNapoli, D-Nassau. Such
regulation could include declaring the craft off-limits on some
waterways and to limit the speed they could go on others, sponsors
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some communities don't mind them, in some places they are used
to attract tourists,'' said DiNapoli, Assembly sponsor of the
measure. ''But other communities will want to preserve the
quietude.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Adirondack Council, John Sheehan, said
localities would be able to put local regulations in place far more
quickly than the state could do it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would definitely take a decade or more to do it centrally''
by the state, Sheehan said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would apply to all navigable waterways in the state.
Villages, towns and cities currently have the right to limit some
personal watercraft usage, but they cannot ban it entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not a one-size-fits-all,'' said Neil Woodworth of the
Adirondack Mountain Club.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would not allow for countywide ''Jet Ski''
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is also supported by the state Conference of Mayors,
the state Association of Towns and other municipal officials
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The local regulation bill will win final legislative approval
Thursday as lawmakers wind down their 2000 regular session,
sponsors predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Another ''Jet Ski'' bill was also passed by both the Assembly
and Senate Thursday. It would require the state Department of
Environmental Conservation to adopt emissions standards for ''Jet
Skis'' above the federal limits set in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The measure directs that emissions standards created by
California in 1998 should also be adopted in New York. They call
for personal watercraft to be 65 percent cleaner than the what the
federal government is requiring for the crafts.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Robert Boyle, a Suffolk County Republican, said the
emissions' measure goes too far.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're asking for an industry to meet standards that they're
simply not able to meet,'' Boyle said. ''Right now they do not have
the technology. You're asking them to get to a place that they
can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Assemblywoman Naomi Matusow, D-Westchester, said personal
watercraft makers do have the ability to make the ''cleaner''
crafts.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists estimate that between 20 percent and 30
percent of the gasoline-oil mixture used to power the two-stroke
personal watercraft engines gets into the water. The air emissions
from the engines is also far dirtier than an automobile's, sponsors
said.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that there are 50,000 personal watercraft in New
York and that twice as many people operate those crafts.
</P>
<P>
   The bills represent the second and third major moves this year
in New York to regulate personal watercraft.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the state Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic
Preservation adopted a system to require that everyone operating a
personal watercraft must have taken a safety course by 2004. The
safety course requirement is being phased in this year, with those
between ages 10 and 19 needing to take the class before being
allowed to operate a craft.
</P>
<P>
   The safety courses were introduced in response to the
disproportionately higher numbers of people injured in personal
watercraft accidents than in other types of boating activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-22-00 2304 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
