<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-22 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.H. Justice Testifies in Trial  </HEADLINE>
By GENE JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- In his final chance to fight off
impeachment, New Hampshire's top judge said he did not report
possible misconduct by a colleague last year because he was not
entirely aware of it.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice David Brock told lawmakers Thursday that he did
not hear any inappropriate remarks made by then-Justice Stephen
Thayer on a case he was disqualified from deciding.
</P>
<P>
   Thayer resigned from the court after he was accused of trying to
influence assignments to an appeals panel hearing his divorce case.
</P>
<P>
   The state House Judiciary Committee is investigating whether
Brock, Justice John Broderick and Justice Sherman Horton should be
impeached over alleged widespread ethics violations.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses have depicted a pattern of Brock putting the court's
right to confidentiality over the need to report misconduct. The
state's Code of Judicial Conduct requires judges to report
wrongdoing by other judges and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Brock said Thursday that reporting misconduct trumps the court's
secrecy rules.
</P>
<P>
   Brock was not questioned Thursday about Thayer's conduct in his
divorce case. The committee members focused on Thayer's conduct in
a case he was disqualified from last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the case, the court was deciding punishments for two lawyers
accused of ethics violations. The lawyer who lodged the complaints
had loaned Thayer $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee is expected to vote July 5 on whether
the justices should be impeached, reprimanded or cleared. The House
will vote on the committee's recommendation July 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-22-00 2311 </TRAILER>
