<HEADLINE> Padres' Gomez Examined for Surgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Chris Gomez of the San Diego Padres, who lost
his starting shortstop job in spring training, had an MRI on his
left knee on Thursday and is due to undergo season-ending surgery
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Nicholson, the Padres' first-round draft pick in 1997,
will be promoted from Triple-A Las Vegas on Friday when Gomez goes
on the disabled list, and is expected to see extensive playing
time. Damian Jackson, who beat out Gomez in the spring, has
committed 14 errors.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez flew from Phoenix to Vail, Colo., on Thursday to have the
knee examined by Dr. Richard Steadman. There's a 99-percent chance
he needs surgery due to bad cartilage, Padres assistant general
manager Fred Uhlman Jr. said Thursday night from Cincinnati, where
the Padres open a three-game series on Friday. Steadman will
determine which procedure Gomez needs after reading the MRI results
a second time on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez will return to San Diego for the weekend, then fly back to
Vail on Monday or Tuesday for surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez underwent arthroscopic surgery on both knees on June 4,
1999, and returned after missing 52 games.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson was the first Canadian to be picked in the first round
of baseball's amateur draft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
